title: Towards the quantum exceptional series

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We find a single two-parameter skein relation on trivalent graphs, the quantum exceptional relation, that specializes to a skein relation associated to each exceptional Lie algebra (in the adjoint representation). If a slight strengthening of Deligne's conjecture on the existence of a (classical) exceptional series is true, then this relation holds for a new two-variable quantum exceptional polynomial, at least as a power series near $q=1$. The single quantum exceptional relation can be viewed as a deformation of the Jacobi relation, and implies a deformation of the Vogel relation that motivated the conjecture on the classical exceptional series.

We find a conjectural basis for the space of diagrams with $n$ loose ends modulo the quantum exceptional relation for $n \leq 6$, with dimensions agreeing with the classical computations, and compute the matrix of inner products, and the quantum dimensions of idempotents. We use the skein relation to compute the conjectural quantum exceptional polynomial for many knots. In particular we determine (unconditionally) the values of the quantum polynomials for the exceptional Lie algebras on these knots. We can perform these computations for all links of Conway width less than 6 , which includes all prime knots with 12 or fewer crossings. Finally, we prove several specialization results relating our conjectural family to certain quantum group categories, and conjecture a number of exceptional analogues of level-rank duality.

# 1. InTRODUCTION 

There are two main 2-variable knot polynomials: the HOMFLY-PT polynomial [FYH*85, PT88] and the Kauffman polynomial [Kau90]. The HOMFLY-PT polynomial interpolates between the Reshetikhin-Turaev invariants [RT90] of the standard representations of the quantum groups $U_{q}\left(\mathfrak{g} I_{n}\right)$, while the Kauffman polynomial does the same for the standard representations of $U_{q}\left(\mathfrak{D}_{n}\right)$ (or, in a slightly different form, the standard representations of $U_{q}\left(\mathfrak{s p}_{n}\right)$ ). The two variable nature of these knot polynomials come from the two parameters $n$ and $q$, but we need to replace the discrete parameter $n$ with a continuous one. One can think of this process in two steps: first construct a family of Lie algebra objects in symmetric ribbon categories which interpolate between the $\mathfrak{g} \mathrm{I}_{n}$ yielding something called $\mathfrak{g I}_{r}$ [DMOS82], and second quantize these Lie algebra objects. This quantization can be done systematically using the Kontsevich integral [BN95], provided it converges.

Work of Cvitanović, Vogel, Deligne, Cohen-de-Man, and others [Cvi08, Del96, DdM96, DG02, CdM96, Vog11, Vog99], can be summarized as a conjecture that there is a third 1-parameter family of Lie algebra objects in symmetric ribbon categories, called the (classical) exceptional series. This should interpolate between the adjoint representations of $\mathfrak{a}_{1}, \mathfrak{a}_{2}, \mathfrak{d}_{4}, \mathfrak{g}_{2}, \mathfrak{f}_{4}, \mathfrak{e}_{6}, \mathfrak{e}_{7}$, and $\mathfrak{e}_{8}$ in an appropriate sense. If this classical exceptional family exists, we should again expect a quantization yielding a 2 -variable exceptional knot invariant $\xi$. In this paper we give a conjectural skein

theoretic description of this exceptional knot invariant. In fact, we prove that these particular skein relations must hold if the exceptional knot invariant exists.

We can use these skein relations to do many computations. In particular, we are able to calculate the value of this knot polynomial (if it exists!) on all knots of Conway width 6, which includes all knots of 12 or fewer crossings. Unconditionally these give the first calculations of the Reshetikhin-Turaev knot invariants for the exceptional Lie algebras for most of these knots. (For 2 - and 3 -strand torus links and for algebraic/arborescent links such calculations can already be found by specializing the calculations done by Mironov-Mkrtchyan-Morozov [MMM16, MM16].) For example, we compute the following value for the left-handed trefoil for the exceptional series, and the Reshetikhin-Turaev invariant for $\mathrm{e}_{8}$ is given by setting $v=q^{5}$ and $w=q^{-1}$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \xi\left(3_{1}\right)=d-\left(v^{6}-v^{-6}\right) d \times \\
& \times\left(v^{34} / w^{4}-v^{44} / w^{4}+v^{36} / w^{2}-v^{40} / w^{2}+v^{44} / w^{2}-v^{46} / w^{2}+v^{50} / w^{2}-v^{54} / w^{2}\right. \\
& -v^{6}-v^{18}+v^{32}+v^{38}-2 v^{42}+v^{46}-v^{50}+v^{52}+v^{54} \\
& \left.+v^{34} w^{2}-v^{38} w^{2}+v^{42} w^{2}-v^{44} w^{2}+v^{48} w^{2}-v^{52} w^{2}+v^{30} w^{4}-v^{40} w^{4}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $d$ is the quantum dimension

$$
d=-\frac{\left(v^{2}+v^{-2}\right)\left(w v^{5}-w^{-1} v^{-5}\right)\left(w v^{-6}-w^{-1} v^{6}\right)}{\left(w-w^{-1}\right)\left(w v^{-1}-w^{-1} v\right)}
$$

We are also able to do several other calculations, like giving quantum dimension formulas for the summands of $\mathfrak{g}^{\otimes 3}$ quantizing the dimension formulas of Cohen-de-Man [CdM96] in the classical case. (For the summands of $\mathfrak{g}^{\otimes 2}$ such quantum dimension formulas were already given by Tuba-Wenzl [TW01].)

In order to state these conjectures and theorems precisely and place them in their proper context, we have written a long introduction split into several subsections.
1.1. The classical exceptional series. We start by giving a skein theoretic description of the classical exceptional series following Cvitanović, Vogel, and Deligne.

We begin with the symmetric ribbon category of Jacobi diagrams, $\mathrm{Jac}_{R, D, B}$.
Definition 1.1. Let $R$ be an algebra over $\mathbb{Q}$, let $D$ be an element of $R$ and let $B$ be an invertible element of $R$. (We use capital letters for these classical quantities; the corresponding quantum quantities will get lowercase letters.) The objects of $\mathrm{Jac}_{R, D, B}$ are collections of $n$ points on the line and the morphism space from $n$ to $m$ consists of $R$-linear combinations of planar graphs in a rectangle with $n$ boundary points on the bottom, $m$ boundary points at the top, and consisting of trivalent vertices and 4 -valent symmetric crossings ${ }^{1}$ modulo planar isotopy, the usual Reidemeister relations for the symmetric crossing and trivalent vertex, and the following circle, lollipop, bigon, triangle, anti-symmetry of the vertex, symmetry of the Killing form, and Jacobi relations.
![img-0.jpeg](img-0.jpeg)

[^0]
[^0]:    ${ }^{1}$ A symmetric crossing means a crossing as in the symmetric group, i.e., not braided.

![img-1.jpeg](img-1.jpeg)

There's an equivalence of ribbon categories $\operatorname{Jac}_{R, D, B} \cong \operatorname{Jac}_{R, D, x B}$ for any invertible $x \in R$ given by isotoping each diagram so every trivalent vertex has two edges coming in from below and one edge going out above and then rescaling by $x$ for each Morse minimum and $x^{-1}$ for each Morse maximum. In particular, if $R=\mathbb{C}$ then $\operatorname{Jac}_{R, D, B}$ does not depend on the choice of $B$. A convenient normalization is $B=12$.

If $\mathfrak{g}$ is a simple Lie algebra object in a symmetric ribbon category with dimension $D$, by the diagram calculus the symmetric ribbon category of finite dimensional representations of $\mathfrak{g}$ is the target of a functor from $\operatorname{Jac}_{R, D, B}$, where we interpret each strand as a copy of $\mathfrak{g}$, each cup or cap using the Killing form or its inverse, each trivalent vertex as the Lie bracket, and each crossing as the usual interchange of tensor factors. The category $\operatorname{Jac}_{R, D, B}$ is somewhat poorly behaved since the space of 0 -boundary point diagrams is infinite dimensional.

Cvitanović [Cvi08] and Vogel [Vog11] independently observed that the adjoint representations of the exceptional Lie algebras satisfy another relation, the classical exceptional relation.
Definition 1.2. If $2+D$ is invertible in $R$, let $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, D, B}$ be the symmetric ribbon category which is the quotient of $\mathrm{Jac}_{R, D, B}$ modulo the exceptional relation

$$
\square=\frac{B}{6}(\square+1) \square+\frac{5}{6} \frac{B^{2}}{2+D}(\square+11
$$

To give nicer formulas, Deligne introduced a parameter $\lambda$ such that $D=-2 \frac{(\lambda+5)(6-\lambda)}{\lambda(1-\lambda)}$ [Del96]. This makes sense so long as $\lambda$ and $1-\lambda$ are invertible in $R$, and such a $\lambda$ can be found when $2+D$ is invertible and $(2+D)(242+D)$ has a square root in $R$. Note that $\lambda$ and $1-\lambda$ correspond to the same $D$ and thus to the same category. If we normalize $B=12$ then the exceptional relation for $\operatorname{Exc}_{R,-2} \frac{(\lambda+5)(6-\lambda)}{\lambda(1-\lambda)}, 12$ (also written $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}$ ) has the form

$$
\square=2(\square+1) \square-2 \lambda(1-\lambda)(\square+111
$$

Let us fix some notation. If $\mathcal{C}$ is a diagram category we denote the Hom space from $k$ points to $\ell$ points by $\mathcal{C}(k, l)$ and the invariant space $\mathcal{C}(k, 0)$ by $\mathcal{C}(k)$. Since all our categories are ribbon, we can use duality to canonically identify $\mathcal{C}(k, l)=\mathcal{C}(n)=\mathcal{C}\left(k^{\prime}, l^{\prime}\right)$ for any $k+l=n=k^{\prime}+l^{\prime}$ by using caps on the right to turn the outputs into inputs. We call this space the $n$-box space. Of course to compose $n$-boxes we need to be careful to turn the appropriate strands back upwards using cups. In some cases, if the notation for $\mathcal{C}$ already involves a parenthesis, we will instead use $\mathcal{C}_{n}$ to denote the $n$-box space, but hopefully this should be clear from context.
Conjecture 1.3 (Classical sufficiency). So long as a certain finite set of non-zero polynomials in $\lambda$ are invertible, the space of $n$-boundary point diagrams in $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}$ is finitely generated as an $R$-module for every $n$. Furthermore, $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}(0)$ is spanned by the empty diagram, $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}(1)$ is the 0 -module, $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}(2)$ is spanned by the strand, $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}(3)$ is spanned by the trivalent vertex, and $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}(4)$ is spanned by
![img-2.jpeg](img-2.jpeg)

![table_0](table_0)

Table 1. Values of $\lambda$ and the supergroup whose category of representations is related to $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda}$. In each case, take the Lie group with trivial center, semidirect product with its group of Dynkin diagram automorphisms.

We also conjecture specific spanning sets for $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}(n)$ for $n \leq 6$; see $\S 5.1$.
Conjecture 1.3 would hold trivially if $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}$ collapsed to the zero category; to address that we have a complementary conjecture.

Conjecture 1.4 (Classical consistency). So long as a certain finite set of non-zero polynomials in $\lambda$ are invertible in $R$, then $R$ injects into $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}(0)$ as multiples of the empty diagram. In particular, any two ways of simplifying the same closed diagram to give an element of $R$ will give the same value.

Remark 1.5. The quantum Conjectures 1.14 and 1.15 below suggest that for Conjectures 1.3 and 1.4 the only polynomials that need to be inverted are $\lambda$ and $1-\lambda$.

Note that if $D=-2 \frac{(\lambda+5)(6-\lambda)}{2(1-\lambda)}$ is invertible in $R$, it follows from classical consistency that $R$ injects into $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}(2)$ as multiples of the strand. If $B$ is also invertible in $R$, it follows from classical consistency that $R$ injects into $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}(3)$ as multiples of the trivalent vertex. Finally if in addition $\lambda \notin\{3,-4\}$ then classical consistency implies that $R^{5}$ injects into $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}(4)$ as linear combinations of the five diagrams in (8). (Lemma 3.14.)

If both consistency and sufficiency hold, it is also natural to conjecture that $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}(n)$ is always a free $R$-module of finite rank.

Proposition 1.6 (Classical specialization). If $G$ is one of the (super)groups on the right of Table 1, and $\lambda$ is the value shown on the left (also equal to $-6 / h^{\vee}$, where $h^{\vee}$ is the dual Coxeter number), then there is a full and dominant functor from $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda}$ to the category of representations of the corresponding group on the right of Table 1.

In particular, the category of representations of the corresponding group on the right of Table 1 is the Cauchy completion (i.e., additive and idempotent completion) of a quotient of $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda}$. This result is in the style of the first fundamental theorem of invariant theory. We would also like an explicit characterization of the kernel of this quotient in the style of the second fundamental theorem of invariant theory, which we do not have. If Conjecture 1.3 holds, then the kernel of this quotient can be characterized abstractly as the tensor ideal of negligible morphisms.

Classical specialization is proved in $\S 6$ following an idea appearing in [Kup96, EN19]. Several cases were already proved in [Mou22].

Conjecture 1.7 (Classical semisimplicity). There is a dense subset $U \subset \mathbb{C}$ so that, for $\lambda \in U$, the Cauchy completion of $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda}$ is semisimple.
(Here as elsewhere, we use the standard, not Zariski, topology on $\mathbb{C}$.) We expect that in order for the Cauchy completion to be semisimple one needs to invert infinitely many polynomials. For example, for the Cauchy completion of $\mathrm{GL}_{t}$ to be semisimple you need to invert $t-n$ for every positive integer $n$. From the dimension formulas of Cohen-de-Man and others, we might speculate that for classical semisimplicity it is enough to invert $k \lambda-\ell$ for $k, \ell \in \mathbb{Z}$. It would follow from Conjecture 1.7 that the Cauchy completion of the generic category $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}(\lambda), \lambda}$ is semisimple.

Deligne's conjecture [Del96] is in terms of the existence of a suitable category. This was improved by Cohen-de-Man [CdM99] who incorporated the Cvitanović-Vogel exceptional relation. We now give a version of their conjecture.

# Conjecture 1.8 (Deligne's conjecture). There exists 

- a ring $R$ which is a localization of $\mathbb{Q}[\lambda]$ at finitely many polynomials;
- a rigid symmetric monoidal category $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}^{D e l}$ where the objects are non-negative integers and morphism spaces are finitely-generated $R$-modules; and
- a symmetric monoidal functor eval from $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}$ to $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}^{D e l}$, that is the identity on objects and surjective on morphisms.
For any map $\varphi: R \rightarrow S$ we can define a base extension $\operatorname{Exc}_{S, \varphi(\lambda)}^{D e l}=\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}^{D e l} \otimes_{\varphi} S$. Furthermore $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda}^{D e l}$ has the following properties for an open dense subset $U \subset \mathbb{C}$.
- The Cauchy completion of $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda}^{D e l}$ is semisimple for $\lambda \in U$.
- $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda}^{D e l}(n)$ has dimension $1,0,1,1,5,16,80$ for $\lambda \in U$ and $n=0,1,2,3,4,5,6$, respectively.
- If $\lambda$ is one of the special values in Table 1, then the Cauchy completion of the quotient of $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda}^{D e l}$ by negligible elements is equivalent to the category of representations of the corresponding supergroup.
Conjecture 1.8 follows from Conjectures 1.3, 1.4, and 1.7 (using Proposition 1.16). Conjecture 1.8 should be viewed as closer to Conjecture 1.4, since it doesn't say anything about the kernel of eval; Conjecture 1.3 says that the classical exceptional relation is the only skein relation needed to define $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}^{D e l}$.

Remark 1.9. We have learned that Vogel has computational evidence against Deligne's conjecture (private communication). Note that it is possible for the quantum Conjectures 1.14 and 1.15 to hold even if the classical conjectures do not. See Remark 1.23.
1.2. Laurent polynomial conventions. The bulk of this paper deals with quantum versions of the sufficiency and consistency conjectures, now involving two variables $v$ and $w .{ }^{2}$ Before stating these conjectures we fix some notation for certain Laurent polynomials appearing in our formulas. On the one hand, we would like to use formulas that are irreducible as Laurent polynomials in $v$ and $w$, so that we can easily read off which primes need to be inverted. On the other hand the Laurent polynomials that occur in our formulas are often even or odd under $v \leftrightarrow v^{-1}$ and/or $w \leftrightarrow w^{-1}$, so we would also like our formulas to have this symmetry. So we often combine two irreducible factors into a single expression. For example, $v-v^{-1}=v^{-1}(v-1)(v+1)=$ $\left(v^{\frac{1}{2}}-v^{-\frac{1}{2}}\right)\left(v^{\frac{1}{2}}+v^{-\frac{1}{2}}\right)$ but there is no way to factor it into odd or even Laurent polynomials so we

[^0]
[^0]:    ${ }^{2}$ We avoid the letter $q$, because the relation of our parameters to the quantum group parameters is not obvious; see $\S 6.6$.

will leave $v-v^{-1}$ alone in our formulas. This will never cause any confusion since any time the irreducible factor $(v-1)$ appears it will have a corresponding $(v+1)$ factor.

Definition 1.10. We define

$$
\begin{aligned}
{[k \lambda+n] } & =w^{k} v^{n}-w^{-k} v^{-n} \\
\{k \lambda+n\} & =\frac{[2 k \lambda+2 n]}{[k \lambda+n]}=w^{k} v^{n}+w^{-k} v^{-n}
\end{aligned}
$$

Warning 1.11. Unlike with the usual quantum numbers, there is no denominator. To get suitable limiting behavior, we need equal number of terms in the numerator and denominator:

$$
\lim _{\substack{v, w \rightarrow 1 \\ w=v^{2}}} \frac{[a \lambda+b]}{[c \lambda+d]}=\frac{a \lambda+b}{c \lambda+d}
$$

(In this equality, $\lambda$ is a formal variable in expressions of the form $[k \lambda+n]$ and a rational number otherwise.)

Note that $\{k \lambda+n\}$ is always irreducible, while $[k \lambda+n]$ is reducible if $k$ and $n$ have a common factor. (In particular, for $n, k>1$, [1] divides [ $n$ ] and $[k \lambda]$.) When $k=0$ we will generally avoid $[n]$ and instead factor into the following symmetrized cyclotomic polynomials. (Strictly speaking we should use a similar convention for factoring $[k \lambda]$, but this is not needed in practice.) Let

$$
\Psi_{n}(v)=\prod_{\xi: \xi^{n}= \pm 1 \text { and } \xi^{m} \neq \pm 1 \text { for } m<n}\left(v^{\frac{1}{2}}-\xi v^{-\frac{1}{2}}\right)
$$

or, in terms of the usual cyclotomic polynomials $\Phi_{n}$ and Euler's totient function $\varphi$,

$$
\Psi_{n}(v)=v^{-\varphi(n)} \Phi_{n}\left(v^{2}\right)
$$

In particular, when $n$ is odd $\Psi_{n}$ vanishes exactly at primitive $n$th and primitive $2 n$th roots of unity, while when $n$ is even, $\Psi_{n}$ vanishes exactly at primitive $2 n$th roots of unity. The notation $\{k \lambda+n\}$ can be viewed as another case of this: $\{k \lambda+n\}=\Psi_{2}\left(w^{k} v^{n}\right)$, and for $n$ a power of $2,\{n\}=\Psi_{2 n}(v)$. For convenience, here are the values of $\Psi_{n}$ that appear in this paper.

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\Psi_{1}(v)=[1]=v-v^{-1} & \Psi_{2}(v)=\{1\}=v+v^{-1} \\
\Psi_{3}(v)=\frac{[3]}{[1]}=v^{2}+1+v^{-2} & \Psi_{4}(v)=\{2\}=v^{2}+v^{-2} \\
\Psi_{5}(v)=\frac{[5]}{[1]}=v^{4}+v^{2}+1+v^{-2}+v^{-4} & \Psi_{6}(v)=\frac{[6][1]}{[3][2]}=v^{2}-1+v^{-2} \\
\Psi_{7}(v)=\frac{[7]}{[1]}=v^{6}+v^{4}+v^{2}+1+v^{-2}+v^{-4}+v^{-6} & \Psi_{8}(v)=\{4\}=v^{4}+v^{-4} \\
\Psi_{10}(v)=\frac{[10][1]}{[5][2]}=v^{4}-v^{2}+1-v^{-2}+v^{-4} & \Psi_{12}(v)=\frac{[12][2]}{[6][4]}=v^{4}-1+v^{-4}
\end{array}
$$

1.3. Quantum exceptional conjectures. We now turn to our main conjectures. Our first goal is to give a definition of a ribbon category QExc which looks like a quantum deformation of Exc. In particular we need skein relations which deform the Jacobi relation, the classical exceptional relation, and the symmetric relation between the overcrossing and undercrossing. Our specific choices of relations will be motivated below by our main theorems.

Definition 1.12. Let $R$ be an algebra over $\mathbb{Q}$ and $v$ and $w$ invertible elements of $R$ such that $[\lambda]$, $[\lambda-1], \Psi_{1}$, and $\Psi_{6}$ are invertible. Let $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}$ be the ribbon category whose objects are collections of $n$ points on a line, and whose morphisms spaces from $n$ to $m$ consist of $R$-linear combinations of planar graphs in a rectangle with $n$ boundary points on the bottom, $m$ boundary points at the top, and consisting of trivalent vertices and 4 -valent braided crossings modulo planar isotopy, the usual Reidemeister 2 and 3 relations for a crossing, the "Reidemeister 2.5" relation saying you can pull a trivalent vertex through a crossing, and the following circle, lollipop, bigon, triangle, quantum anti-symmetry, and quantum Killing symmetry relations.
![img-3.jpeg](img-3.jpeg)
where

$$
\begin{aligned}
d & =-\frac{\Psi_{4}[\lambda+5][\lambda-6]}{[\lambda][\lambda-1]} \\
b & =\{\lambda+2\}\{\lambda-3\} \Psi_{3} \\
t & =\Psi_{2}\left(\Psi_{2}\{2 \lambda-1\}+\left(v^{4}-v^{2}-1-v^{-2}+v^{-4}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

To these skein relations, we add three more relations:

- the quantum exceptional Jacobi relation
$(\mathrm{QEJac}-\mathrm{w}) v^{-3} \bigodot+v \bigodot-v^{-1} \bigodot-\frac{[\lambda][\lambda-1]}{\Psi_{1}} \bigcap+v^{4} \bigodot+v^{-4} \bigcap=0$.
- the quantum exceptional square relation
$(\mathrm{QESq}-\mathrm{w}) \bigodot+\frac{-\Psi_{2} \Psi_{6}^{2}[\lambda][\lambda-1]}{\Psi_{1}^{2}} \bigvee+\frac{x_{1}}{\Psi_{1}} \bigvee+\frac{x_{2}}{\Psi_{1}} \bigvee+\frac{x_{3}}{\Psi_{1}^{2}}+\frac{x_{4}}{\Psi_{1}^{2}} \bigcap=0$
where the $x_{i}$ are Laurent polynomials in $v$ and $w$ from Appendix A.
- the quantum exceptional crossing relation
$(\mathrm{QECross}-\mathrm{w}) \bigvee-\bigvee+\frac{\Psi_{1}}{\Psi_{6}} \bigcap-\bigvee \bigcap+\frac{\Psi_{1}[\lambda][\lambda-1]}{\Psi_{6}} \bigcap(-\bigwedge]=0$.
Note that if you set $w=v^{\lambda}$ and take the limit $v \rightarrow 1$ these relations recover the classical Jacobi relation, classical exceptional relation, and the relation in a symmetric tensor category saying that the overcrossing equals the undercrossing. In order to make this specialization process purely algebraic, we would need to introduce a larger ring with formal symbols for expressions like $\frac{w-w^{-1}}{v-v^{-1}}$.

Warning 1.13. Although (QEJac-w) looks like an analogue of the ordinary Jacobi relation with lower order terms, it is important to emphasize that it is only the correct analogue of the Jacobi relation in the exceptional setting. In particular, we do not expect any similar relation for quantizations of non-exceptional Lie algebras.

We now state our main conjectures. Let $\mathbf{P}$ be the set of Laurent polynomials in $v, w$

$$
\mathbf{P}=\left\{v, w, \Psi_{1}, \Psi_{2}, \Psi_{3}, \Psi_{6},[\lambda],[1-\lambda]\right\}
$$

(This list includes the polynomials that we assume to be invertible to define $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}$.)
Conjecture 1.14 (Quantum sufficiency). If the polynomials in $\mathbf{P}$ are invertible in $R$, the space of $n$ boundary point diagrams in $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}$ is finitely generated as an $R$-module for every $n$. Furthermore, $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}(0)$ is generated by the empty diagram, $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}(1)$ is the zero module, $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}(2)$ is generated by the strand, $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}(3)$ is generated by the trivalent vertex, and $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}(4)$ is generated by
![img-4.jpeg](img-4.jpeg)

As before we have conjectured spanning sets for $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}(n)$ for $n=0,1,2,3,4,5,6$; see Conjecture 5.1.

Conjecture 1.15 (Quantum consistency). So long as the polynomials in $\mathbf{P}$ are invertible, $R$ injects into $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}$ as multiples of the empty diagram. In particular, any two ways of applying the above relations to a closed diagram to return a rational function in $v$ and $w$ will yield the same rational function.

As in the classical case, from this conjecture we get that if $d$ (resp. $d$ and $b$ ) are invertible, then $R$ also injects into $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}(2)$ (resp. $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}(3)$ ) as multiples of the strand (resp. trivalent vertex), and under some other invertibility assumptions $R^{S}$ injects into $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}(4)$ as linear combinations of the five diagrams in (10) (see Lemma 3.10).

Proposition 1.16 (Quantum specialization). If $\lambda$ is one of the values on the left of Table 1, then there is a full and dominant functor from $\mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}, v, v^{\lambda}}$ to the category of representations of the quantum version of the corresponding group, for $v$ in some dense subset of $\mathbb{C}$.

As before, the category of representations of the corresponding group on the right of Table 1 is the Cauchy completion of a quotient of $\mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}, v, v^{\lambda}}$. If Conjecture 1.3 holds, then the kernel of this quotient can be characterized abstractly as the tensor ideal of negligible morphisms.

We expect that quantum specialization holds for all $v$ that are not roots of unity. This conjecture could also be stated more algebraically by working over the generic point $\mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}(v), v, v^{\lambda}}$. Moreover, if you replace the quantum group category with the appropriate tilting modules at roots of unity, then it should hold except at some small roots of unity.

Quantum specialization is stated precisely and proved as Proposition 6.97 in $\S 6.6$, again following an idea appearing in [EN19]. (The precise statement has the correspondence between the parameters $q$ and $v$, which is somewhat subtle.)
Conjecture 1.17 (Quantum semisimplicity). There is an open dense subset $U \subset \mathbb{C}^{2}$ for which the Cauchy completion of $\mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}, v, w}$, for $(v, w) \in U$, is semisimple.

We expect that it's enough to assume that $[k \lambda+\ell]$ is nonzero for all integers $k$ and $\ell$ (in particular, $v$ is not a root of unity).

To justify the definition of the QExc we have the following theorems, which we can summarize as saying that under some mild assumptions, any trivalent ribbon category where the $n$-box space has dimension at most $1,0,1,1,5$ for $n=0,1,2,3,4$ satisfies a version of (QEJac-w). Furthermore, again under some mild assumptions, (QEJac-w) implies (QESq-w) and (QECross-w). To allow for more general statements, we use another set of variables, $(v, \alpha)$ in place of $(v, w)$ above, at the cost of messier formulas.

Definition 1.18. A trivalent ribbon category $(\mathcal{C}, X, \tau)$ is a ribbon category $\mathcal{C}$ over $R$ with an object $X$ where

- the 1-box space is zero, and
- the $0-, 2-$, and 3 -box spaces are rank 1 free $R$-modules generated by the empty diagram, the strand, and a 'trivalent vertex' $\tau \in \mathcal{C}(3)$ respectively,
such that
- the category is generated as a ribbon category by $\tau$,
- the value of the circle is a non-zero multiple $d$ of the empty diagram, and
- the value of the bigon is a non-zero multiple $b$ of the strand.

Being generated as a ribbon category by $\tau$ is the same as saying that $\mathcal{C}$ is generated as a pivotal category by $\tau$ and the crossing. In particular, a trivalent ribbon category need not be trivalent in the sense of [MPS17] where the trivalent vertex alone is assumed to generate $\mathcal{C}$ as a pivotal category. Also we have weakened the non-degeneracy condition from [MPS17], replacing it with the assumption that the circle and bigon are non-zero.

Theorem 1. Suppose $(\mathcal{C}, X, \tau)$ is a trivalent ribbon category over $\mathbb{C}$ and $\operatorname{dim} \mathcal{C}(4) \leq 5$. Then there exists $v, \alpha, b, d, t \in \mathbb{C}$ such that the relations in (9) hold with

$$
\begin{aligned}
& {[5] b=-\alpha(d+\{8\})} \\
& \text { \{2\} } t=b-[5] \alpha
\end{aligned}
$$

as well as
$(\mathrm{QEJac}-\alpha)$

$$
v^{-3}+v+v^{2}-v^{-1} \quad+\alpha \quad+v^{4}+v^{-4} \quad \text { 1 }=0 .
$$

If $\operatorname{dim} \mathcal{C}(4)=5$ then relation (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) is the only relation of this form up to simultaneously sending $v \mapsto-v$ and $\alpha \mapsto-\alpha$, but if $\operatorname{dim} \mathcal{C}(4)<5$ then there will be at least two linearly independent such relations.

Theorem 2. Suppose $(\mathcal{C}, X, \tau)$ is a trivalent ribbon category over $\mathbb{C}$ with $\operatorname{dim} \mathcal{C}(4) \leq 5$ and there exist $v$ and $\alpha$ satisfying (QEJac- $\alpha$ ), with $v^{10} \neq 1$ and $v^{12} \neq 1$. Then $\alpha$ and $b+[3] \alpha$ are also non-zero, $v^{8} \neq 1$, and we have the following relations:

- $d=-\frac{[5] b}{[2]}-[8]$.
- $t=\frac{b-[5] \alpha}{[2]}$.
- The quantum exceptional square relation:
$(\mathrm{QESq}-\alpha)$
![img-5.jpeg](img-5.jpeg)
where the $y_{i}$ are Laurent polynomials in $b, \alpha$, and $v$ given in Appendix A.

- The quantum exceptional crossing relation:
(QECross- $\alpha$ )

$$
\left.\left.1-\frac{\Psi_{1} \Psi_{2} \Psi_{3} \Psi_{4}}{b+[3] \alpha}\right| \cdots\right\rangle\left.\left.1-\frac{\Psi_{1}^{2} \Psi_{2} \Psi_{3} \Psi_{4} \alpha}{b+[3] \alpha}\right| \cdots\right\rangle=0 .
$$

To get back to the $(v, w)$ variables and nicer formulas in Definition 1.12, we make a change of variables motivated by the Kontsevich integral approach and Deligne's change of variable from $d$ to $\lambda$. (See Lemma 3.12 for an alternate motivation.) We first remind the reader of some very elementary mathematics which we nonetheless found quite confusing.

Remark 1.19. Consider the rational change of variables from $(x, y)$ to $(x, w)$ with $w=\frac{y}{x+y}$, which makes sense when $y \neq-x$. The inverse change of variables is given by the rational function $y=\frac{w x}{1-w}$, which makes sense when $w \neq 1$. However, in order for these transformations to be inverse we need to check that

$$
y \stackrel{?}{=} \frac{x \frac{y}{x+y}}{1-\frac{y}{x+y}}=\frac{x y}{x}
$$

which requires in addition that $x \neq 0$. In this case, $y$ as a function of $w$ and vice versa are fractional linear transformations, which are invertible as long as the determinant of the corresponding $2 \times 2$ matrix $\left(\begin{array}{ll}1 & 0 \\ 1 & x\end{array}\right)$ is nonzero. More generally, by the inverse function theorem the transformation $(x, y) \mapsto(x, w)$ fails to have an inverse exactly when $\partial_{y} w=\frac{(x+y)-y}{(x+y)^{2}}=0$.

When $b+[3] \alpha$ is non-zero and the relevant square roots exist in $R$ we can make the change of variables from $\alpha$ to $w$ given by

$$
\frac{w^{2}}{v}+\frac{v}{w^{2}}=\frac{\{1\} b-[3\}\{5\} \alpha}{b+[3] \alpha}
$$

Note that there are generically four values of $w$ for each value of $\alpha$. We see that $\partial_{\alpha}\left(w^{2} / v+v / w^{2}\right)=$ 0 exactly if $0=\{1\} \cdot[3]+1 \cdot[3]\{5\}=\Psi_{1} \Psi_{2} \Psi_{3} \Psi_{4} \Psi_{6}$, so when $v$ is not an 8 th or 12 th root of unity the (multi-valued) change of variables is invertible, with (single-valued) inverse given by

$$
\alpha=-\frac{b[\lambda][\lambda-1]}{\{\lambda+2\}\{\lambda-3\} \Psi_{1} \Psi_{3}}
$$

Finally, we observe that if we rescale the choice of self-duality so that $b=\{\lambda+2\}\{\lambda-3\} \Psi_{3}$, formulas (QEJac- $\alpha$ ), (QESq- $\alpha$ ), and (QECross- $\alpha$ ) are generically identical to the formulas in terms of $v, w$ given earlier as (QEJac-w), (QESq-w) and (QECross-w).

Corollary 1.20. Suppose $(\mathcal{C}, X, \tau)$ is a trivalent ribbon category over $\mathbb{C}$ with $\operatorname{dim} \mathcal{C}(4) \leq 5$ so that (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) holds with $v^{10} \neq 1$ and $v^{12} \neq 1$. Then, there is a $w \in \mathbb{C}$ and an evaluation functor $\mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}, v, w} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$ sending the trivalent vertex to $\tau$.

This corollary justifies our definition of QExc, since if the quantum exceptional family exists in any form it would have to satisfy our quantum exceptional relations.

Remark 1.21. Throughout the paper, when we say that "(QEJac- $\alpha$ ) holds" in a trivalent ribbon category, we implicitly include the choice of $v$ and the elementary relations (9) in the statement.

1.4. From classical to quantum. The classical conjectures from $\S 1.1$ and the quantum conjectures from $\S 1.3$ are related, but there are no formal implications between them. From the point of view of the quantum conjectures, the classical specialization $v=1$ is excluded by the assumption that $\Psi_{1}$ is invertible. There is a partial implication the other direction: Conjecture 1.8 implies a corresponding quantum conjecture.

Conjecture 1.22 (Quantum version of Deligne's conjecture). There exists

- a ring $R$ satisfying the hypotheses of Definition 1.12;
- a trivalent ribbon category $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}^{\text {Del }}$ where the objects are non-negative integers and morphism spaces are finitely-generated $R$-modules; and
- a ribbon functor Qeval from $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}$ to $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}^{\text {Del }}$, that is the identity on objects, surjective on morphisms, and sends the trivalent vertex to the trivalent vertex.

Theorem 3. If Conjecture 1.8 is true for $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}^{\text {Del }}$, then Conjecture 1.22 is true for $\operatorname{Exc}_{R((h)), v, w}^{\text {Del }}$ for $v=e^{h / 2}$ and $w=e^{\lambda h / 2}$ as formal Laurent series.

In interpreting Theorem 3, recall that we normalized $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}$ so $B=12$. In the language introduced in $\S 2.2$, this normalization of $B$ corresponds to what we call the "Convenient" choice of invariant inner product.

Theorem 3 is proved in $\S 4$.
1.5. Calculations. In $\S 5$ we calculate some properties of $\mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}, v, w}$ and the corresponding 2variable knot polynomial, under the assumptions of our main conjectures.

First we give conjectural bases for the box spaces up to $n=6$, and check that these diagrams are linearly independent (assuming Conjecture 1.4). We unconditionally give a 16-dimensional representation of the 5 -strand affine braid group, and an 80 -dimensional representation of the 6 -strand affine braid group, obtained from the braid group actions on these 5- and 6-boundary point diagrams.

Using this, we give a divide-and-conquer algorithm for computing the conjectural quantum exceptional invariant of all knotted trivalent graphs of Conway width at most 6 . This includes all prime knots of at most 12 crossings, and nearly all prime links of at most 12 crossings, including many non-algebraic examples.

Note that without assuming any of our conjectures, by Proposition 1.16 these 2-variable knot polynomials must specialize at particular values of $w$ to give the quantum invariants of the adjoint representations of the actual Lie algebras. To our knowledge these are the first calculations of the quantum knot polynomials of non-torus knots for the adjoint representations of any of the exceptional Lie algebras, and they are much more efficient than doing the calculations directly in $U_{\mathrm{g}}(\mathfrak{g})$. (For torus knots these calculations can be done using the Rosso-Jones formula [RJ93], see [MMM16].)

Using our skein relations, we also compute the quantum versions of Cohen-de-Man's [CdM96] formulas for the dimensions of the objects appearing in the third tensor power of adjoint representation in the exceptional series. (For the summands of $\mathfrak{g}^{\otimes 2}$ such quantum dimension formulas were already given by Tuba-Wenzl [TW05].)

The programs internally work with formulas $\mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}, v, \alpha}$, since the degrees are smaller.
1.6. Symmetries and the parameter plane. For reference, we list some global symmetries of the category $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}$. Consider the following involutions on our parameters:

![table_1](table_1)

Of these, symmetries (12) and (13) do not change any of the skein relations. The first is an artifact of the parameterization, and specifically our insistence on formulas that are balanced under $w \leftrightarrow w^{-1}$. The second interchanges the roles of $\lambda$ and $1-\lambda$ in the quantum number formulas, and is thus a quantization of the symmetry of $\operatorname{Exc}_{R, \lambda}$ interchanging $\lambda$ and $1-\lambda$. For instance it switches two eigenvalues of the twist acting on the 4 -box space (Lemma 3.12).

Symmetry (14) rescales $b$ by -1 , as explained in $\S 1.1$. Specifically it acts on diagrams in $D$ with $n$ incoming vertices, $m$ outgoing vertices, and $k$ trivalent vertices by

$$
D \mapsto(-1)^{(m-n+k) / 2} \cdot D
$$

Symmetry (15) acts on diagrams by reflecting in the plane of the knot diagram, switching the sign of all crossings. (The powers of $v$ appearing in (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) were chosen so that $\alpha$ does not change under this reflection.)

These symmetries generate a group of order 16. (Symmetries (13) and (14) do not commute). If we restrict the action to the torus $v=e^{i \theta}$ and $w=e^{i \varphi}$ for real $\theta, \varphi$, one fundamental domain for the group is

$$
\begin{aligned}
0 & \leq \theta \leq \pi / 2 \\
(\theta-\pi) / 2 & \leq \varphi \leq \theta / 2
\end{aligned}
$$

as shown in Figure 1, along with the lines $w=v^{\lambda}$ corresponding to the exceptional series and certain other lines explained in $\S 6.7$.
1.7. Special values. In $\S 6$, we look at what happens in certain special cases. For many of these special cases the change of variables is not well-defined, so we will often need to return to the $\alpha$-version of the main relations.

We begin by outlining how to prove specialization theorems in the style of Proposition 1.6, using ideas from Kuperberg's paper [Kup96, Thm. 5.1], as expanded on by [EN19, Thms. 2.1 and 2.3] and [GSZ23, Thm. 5.3].

Second in $\S 6.2$, we collect and expand upon some results about Deligne's symmetric group category, the classical $G 2$ and $F 4$ families, and the relationship between these three categories and Frobenius algebras, Hurwitz algebras, and cubic Cayley-Hamilton Jordan algebras.

Third, we write down explicitly which instances of the quantum exceptional relation hold in various special cases where $\operatorname{dim} \mathcal{C}(4)<5$ and so multiple relations hold.

Fourth, when $v$ is a 10th or 12th root of unity, Corollary 1.20 does not apply. We show that when $v= \pm 1$ then the classical exceptional relations must hold (see [Mou22] for some related results). We show that when $v= \pm i$ and an additional non-degeneracy assumption holds, the relations of the classical $F 4$ series must hold (see [GSZ23] for some related results). Finally we show that when $v$ is a primitive 3 rd or 6 th root of unity, then the relations of the classical $G 2$ series must hold (see [Boo98, Wes10, Str19, Bae01] for related results). We delay a full treatment of all root of unity cases to later work.

![img-6.jpeg](img-6.jpeg)

Figure 1. A fundamental domain for the action of symmetries on $(v, w)$, restricted to the torus $|v|=|w|=1$. The left side is glued to itself by $(v, w) \leftrightarrow(1 / v, w / v)$, the top by $(v, w) \leftrightarrow(v, v / w)$, the bottom by $(v, w) \leftrightarrow(v,-v / w)$, and the top of the right side is glued to the bottom of the right side by $(v, w) \leftrightarrow(-1 / v, 1 / w)$. The colored solid lines are the loci $w=v^{\lambda}$ and their symmetric images, for $\lambda$ one of the values in Table 1. The dashed red lines are loci where denominators in the definition of QExc vanish. The dashed brown lines are the loci where either $d=0$ or $b=0$. This figure also includes other known specializations (§6.7), and there are other loci that are exceptions to the main theorems (Figure 2).

We prove the classical and quantum specialization results for the exceptional family in $\S 6.6$. Then in $\S 6.7$ we prove analogous results for the $G 2$ and $F 4$ families; see $\S 6.2$ for background on the classical $G 2$ and $F 4$ families, each of which has several specializations to Lie (super)groups.

Finally we conjecture a number of coincidences of quantum group categories.
Remark 1.23. The category $\mathrm{Q} \mathrm{Exc}_{R, n, w}$, viewed in this paper as a quantized version of the conjectural exceptional family, can also be viewed as a quantization of the $F 4$ family. Indeed, the main difference between the classical exceptional and $F 4$ families is whether the generating trivalent vertex is anti-symmetric or symmetric, and thus the relation (QEJac-w) can be viewed as a quantum deformation of the defining $F 4$ relation from Definition 6.41. The fact that the classical consistency fails for the $F 4$ family [Thu05] (see §6.2.3) has no implications about quantum consistency for $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, n, w}$. Such an interpretation doesn't really work for the classical $G 2$ family, since the 4 -box space for the classical $G 2$ family only has dimension 4.
1.8. Other work. There has been a great deal of work on the classical (1-parameter) exceptional series and the larger (2-parameter) Vogel plane, but relatively little on the quantized versions. On one level, some previous work has calculated universal knot invariants, which can be thought of as the knot invariants coming from the putative quantized Vogel plane, hence giving specializations to the quantum knot invariants of any adjoint representation, exceptional or not. Mironov-Mkrtchyan-Morozov [MMM16] explain the calculation of the universal knot invariants for all 2and 3-strand torus knots. Westbury [Wes15] explains the context of the quantized Vogel plane, and gives the invariants for $(2, n)$ torus knots (in $\S 6.1$ of that paper). Mironov-Morozov [MM16] explain how to calculate the universal invariants for all algebraic (a.k.a. arborescent) links. Note that the class we calculate includes many non-algebraic links. The first is $8_{18}$; see Appendix B.

Finally, Westbury uses similar techniques [Wes22, §4] in a related context with two different types of strands.
1.9. Acknowledgements. KM was partially supported by Discovery Project grants 'Subfactors and symmetries' DP140100732 and 'Low dimensional categories' DP160103479, and a Future Fellowship 'Quantum symmetries' FT170100019 from the Australian Research Council. NS was supported by NSF grants DMS-1454767 and DMS-2000093, and would like to thank MSRI where some of this work was done; research at MSRI is supported in part by NSF grant DMS-1928930. DPT was supported by NSF grants DMS-1008049, DMS-1507244, and DMS-2110143. Thanks to Joshua Chen, whose algorithms we used in drawing some of the figures in this paper. Thanks to Emily Peters, Alistair Savage, Pierre Vogel, and Bruce Westbury for helpful conversations, and to the referee for helpful comments.

sections.text:
# 2. BACKGROUND 

2.1. Trivalent tangles and braided trivalent categories. Let $R$ be a ring and let $\mathrm{Tri}_{R}$ denote the ribbon category of $R$-linear combinations of framed unoriented knotted trivalent graphs. That is, its objects are points on the line, and its morphisms are formal linear combinations of framed unoriented knotted trivalent graphs with composition given by vertical gluing, and tensor product given by horizontal disjoint union. Note in particular that the trivalent vertex is rotationally invariant.

Suppose that $X$ is an object in a ribbon category $\mathcal{C}$ over $R, s: X \rightarrow X^{*}$ is a self-duality (i.e., one where $\left(p_{x}\right)^{-1} \circ s^{*}=s$ where $p_{X}: X \rightarrow X^{* *}$ is the pivotal structure), and $\tau: X \otimes X \rightarrow X$ is a map which is rotationally invariant in the sense that the map

$$
X \otimes X \rightarrow X \otimes X \otimes X \otimes X^{*} \rightarrow X^{*} \otimes X \otimes X \rightarrow X
$$

given by

$$
(\mathrm{ev} \otimes \mathrm{id}) \circ\left(s \otimes \tau \otimes s^{-1}\right) \circ(\mathrm{id} \otimes \mathrm{id} \otimes \text { coev })
$$

is equal to $\tau$. Then the ribbon diagram calculus [Sel11] defines a functor $\operatorname{Tri}_{R} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$ sending the strand to $X$ and the trivalent vertex to $\tau$.

In particular, if $\mathcal{C}$ is a trivalent ribbon category in the sense of Definition 1.18, then by [MPS17, Lemma 2.2], $X$ is symmetrically self-dual, and by [MPS17, Lemma 8.2], the trivalent vertex is rotationally invariant, so we get a ribbon functor as above. This functor depends on a choice of isomorphism $X \rightarrow X^{*}$ and a choice of map $X \otimes X \rightarrow X$, each of which is well-defined up to rescaling.

Similarly, we can consider the symmetric ribbon category $\operatorname{SymTri}_{R}$ of framed unoriented symmetric graphs where we do not distinguish between overcrossings and undercrossings. Again if we have a symmetric ribbon category $\mathcal{C}$ over $R$ with a choice of an object $X$, a symmetric self-duality $s$, and a rotationally invariant map $X \otimes X \rightarrow X$, then we get a functor $\operatorname{SymTri}_{R} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$.

Several of our categories have more than one tensor generator which support a product making it a trivalent ribbon category, giving distinct functors from $\operatorname{Tri}_{R}$. In ambiguous cases we frequently add the tensor generator to disambiguate. For instance, $G_{2}$ arises with both its defining 7dimensional representation, denoted $V_{(1,0)}$ in our weight ordering, and its adjoint 14-dimensional representation $V_{(0,1)}$. Thus $\left(G_{2}, V_{(1,0)}\right)$ and $\left(G_{2}, V_{(0,1)}\right)$ denote the same category $\operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{2}\right)$ but indicate different functors from SymTri, and likewise the quantized versions $\left(G_{2}, V_{(1,0)}\right)_{q}$ and $\left(G_{2}, V_{(0,1)}\right)_{q}$ are the same ribbon category but with different functors from Tri. (In principle we should follow Definition 1.18 and also include the trivalent vertex $\tau$, but in almost all cases the only ambiguity there is the scale, which is mostly fixed by specifying $b$.) We also use $G$ as shorthand for the category $\operatorname{Rep}(G)$, and similarly for the quantized versions.
2.2. Diagrams, Lie algebras, and inner product conventions. Consider the symmetric ribbon category of Jacobi diagrams, $\mathrm{Jac}_{R, D, B}$ from Definition 1.1.

Definition 2.1. A metric Lie algebra object in a symmetric ribbon category $\mathcal{C}$ is an object $\mathfrak{g}$ with a bracket $[\cdot, \cdot]: \mathfrak{g} \otimes \mathfrak{g} \rightarrow \mathfrak{g}$ satisfying the Jacobi identity and antisymmetry, and a symmetric pairing $(\cdot, \cdot): \mathfrak{g} \otimes \mathfrak{g} \rightarrow 1$ which is invariant under the adjoint action and such that there exists (a necessarily unique) copairing $C: 1 \rightarrow \mathfrak{g} \otimes \mathfrak{g}$ exhibiting $\mathfrak{g}$ as its own dual, i.e., satisfying the zig-zag axioms. We will denote the copairing on $\mathfrak{g}^{*}$ using angle brackets, as $\langle\cdot, \cdot\rangle: \mathfrak{g}^{*} \otimes \mathfrak{g}^{*} \rightarrow 1$.

The strand in $\mathrm{Jac}_{R, D, B}$ with the trivalent vertex as the bracket and the cap and cup as the pairing and copairing is a metric Lie algebra object. Moreover it has the following well-known universal property, essentially described by Bar-Natan [BN95].
Lemma 2.2. Suppose $\mathcal{C}$ is a symmetric ribbon category over $R$ with $\operatorname{End}(1)=R$ and $\mathfrak{g}$ a metric Lie algebra object with $\operatorname{End}(\mathfrak{g})=R$. Then there exist $D, B \in R$ and a functor $\mathrm{Jac}_{R, D, B} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$ sending the strand to $\mathfrak{g}$ and preserving the metric Lie algebra structure.

Suppose $\mathfrak{g}$ is a simple Lie algebra over $\mathbb{C}$. Then there exists a $\mathfrak{g}$-invariant bilinear form which is unique up to rescaling. Each choice of such bilinear form makes $\mathfrak{g}$ into a metric Lie algebra and thus gives us a symmetric functor from $\mathrm{Jac}_{R, D, B}$. It's easy to see that $D=\operatorname{dim} \mathfrak{g}$. The value of $B$ will depend on the choice of bilinear form. In particular, rescaling the choice of bilinear form will change the interpretation of a graph by a scalar. If the graph is isotoped so that all trivalent vertices have two strands coming in from below and one from above, then the value of the diagram is homogeneous of degree the number of local maxima in the diagram minus the number of local minima.

More generally given a metric Lie algebra object $\mathfrak{g}$ and a representation object $V$, we can interpret diagrams with unoriented edges labelled by $\mathfrak{g}$, oriented edges labelled by $V$, and trivalent vertices corresponding to both the Lie bracket (satisfying the Jacobi and antisymmetry relations) and to the action of $\mathfrak{g}$ on $V$, satisfying the axioms of an action. (See [BN95, §2.4], though see [CL07] for sign conventions.)

The goal of this section is to compare several conventions for choice of bilinear form on a simple Lie algebra $\mathfrak{g}$, and to do a few simple diagram calculations.

We will be interested in four different invariant bilinear forms on $\mathfrak{g}$ :

- the "Short" form $(x, y)_{S}$ where short roots have squared length 2 ,
- the "Long" form $(x, y)_{L}$ where long roots have squared length 2 ,
- the Killing form $(x, y)_{K}$ defined by $\operatorname{Tr}\left(\operatorname{ad}_{x} \circ \mathrm{ad}_{y}\right)$,
- the "Convenient" form $(x, y)_{C}$ which is $1 / 12$ of the Killing form.

Note that the roots in the definition of the Short and Long form live in $\mathfrak{h}^{*}$ (or its complexification), and use the copairing $\langle\cdot, \cdot\rangle$ on that space (which is a quotient of $\mathfrak{g}^{*}$ ).

The main reason for using all four of these conventions at various times is to use results in the literature which already made a preferred choice. A secondary reason is that when considering the Kontsevich integral it is more natural to use the Killing form or the Convenient form, while for quantum groups it's more natural to use the Short form or the Long form. We will put subscripts on the various quantities that depend on the bilinear forms, notably the bigon parameter $B$; in these contexts, $*$ is a generic subscript that can represent any of the four options.

Remark 2.3. If $\mathfrak{g}$ is a simple Lie superalgebra (i.e., a Lie algebra object in the category of super vector spaces), then we can similarly define a Killing form using the supertrace. However, unlike in the case of simple Lie algebras, for a superalgebra it can happen that the Killing form is identically zero. If the Killing form is non-zero then it is automatically non-degenerate, and we can again make the above definitions. In this paper we will only ever consider Lie superalgebras that have non-zero Killing form. See [FSS00, §23] for a list of which simple Lie superalgebras have zero or non-zero Killing form.

Recall that the Dual Coxeter number $h^{\vee}$ can be defined to be half of the ratio of the Killing form to the Long form [SS70, §4.8] [BZ10], while $\Delta$ (usually denoted $D$, but we use $D$ for certain dimensions) is the lacing number, which is the ratio of the Long form to the Short form. These two facts let us easily determine the ratio between any two of these forms. For example the Convenient form is $h^{\vee} \Delta / 6=-\Delta / \lambda$ times the Short form. (Here $\lambda=-6 / h^{\vee}$ is the parameter from the introduction.) See also Table 2.

Lemma 2.4. For any choice of invariant bilinear form, the following diagram maps to the Killing form in $\operatorname{Rep}(\mathfrak{g}):$

![img-7.jpeg](img-7.jpeg)

Proof. Let $e_{i}$ and $e^{i}$ denote dual bases of $\mathfrak{g}$ with respect to the given form $(\cdot, \cdot)$. The following diagram is isotopic to the one in the statement of the lemma:
![img-8.jpeg](img-8.jpeg)

By the diagram calculus, this diagram maps to the composition

$$
x \otimes y \mapsto \sum_{i} x \otimes y \otimes e_{i} \otimes e^{i} \mapsto x \otimes\left[y, e_{i}\right] \otimes e^{i} \mapsto\left(e^{i},\left[x,\left[y, e_{i}\right]\right]\right)
$$

which is exactly the Killing form.
In particular, we see that with respect to the Killing form the bigon parameter is $B_{K}=1$, and if we rescale the pairing $(\cdot, \cdot)$ by $c$ the copairing and the bigon parameter both scale by $1 / c$.

Definition 2.5. Fix an invariant bilinear form on $\mathfrak{g}$. Suppose that $V$ is an irreducible representation of $\mathfrak{g}$. Define $C_{V}$ to be the eigenvalue of the quadratic Casimir on $V$, i.e., the unique scalar such that

$$
\left\langle\right|=C_{V}
$$

where the unoriented strand is labelled $\mathfrak{g}$, the oriented strand is labelled $V$, and the trivalent vertices are the action map $\mathfrak{g} \otimes V \rightarrow V$. In other words,

$$
\sum_{i} e^{i}\left(e_{i} v\right)=C_{V} v
$$

The quadratic Casimir $C_{V}$ involves a cup and no caps, so scales like the bigon.
Let $\rho \in \mathfrak{h}^{*}$ be the Weyl vector. (In the super case, this is half the sum of positive even roots minus half the sum of the positive odd roots.) The following fact is well-known. (See, e.g., [Kna02, Prop. 5.28] for a proof for $(\cdot, \cdot)_{K}$, and note that the two sides scale the same way as the pairing varies.)

Proposition 2.6. Let $\mu$ be a dominant weight for a simple Lie (super)algebra $\mathfrak{g}$ and $V_{\mu}$ the corresponding highest weight representation. With respect to any form, the eigenvalue of the quadratic Casimir for $V_{\mu}$ is $C_{\mu}:=C_{V_{\mu}}=\langle\mu, \mu+2 \rho\rangle$.

Let $\theta$ denote the highest root, i.e., the highest weight for the adjoint representation. By definition $C_{\theta}=B$. In particular, with respect to the Long form we have $2 h^{\vee}=B_{L}=\langle\theta, \theta+2 \rho\rangle_{L}=$ $2+2\langle\theta, \rho\rangle_{L}$. This gives a second characterization of $h^{\vee}$, namely $h^{\vee}=1+\langle\theta, \rho\rangle_{L}$.

Lemma 2.7. With respect to the Long form, we have $C_{2 \theta, L}=4\left(h^{\vee}+1\right)$.
Proof. We can directly calculate:

$$
C_{2 \theta, L}=\langle 2 \theta, 2 \theta+2 \rho\rangle_{L}=8+4\langle\theta, \rho\rangle_{L}=8+4\left(h^{\vee}-1\right)=4\left(h^{\vee}+1\right)
$$

Finally we will want a few results about the eigenvalues of the ladder operator

$$
\rangle_{\langle\langle} \mid \mathfrak{g} \otimes \mathfrak{g} \rightarrow \mathfrak{g} \otimes \mathfrak{g}
$$

or in other words $\rangle_{\langle}(x, y)=\sum_{i}\left[x, e_{i}\right]\left[e^{i}, x\right]$.
Lemma 2.8. If $V_{\mu}$ is a simple summand of $\mathfrak{g} \otimes \mathfrak{g}$ and $L_{\mu}$ is the eigenvalue of the ladder operator as it acts on $\operatorname{End}(\mathfrak{g} \otimes \mathfrak{g})$ with eigenvector the projection map onto $V_{\mu}$, then

$$
C_{\mu}=2 B-2 L_{\mu}
$$

(This equation is homogeneous in rescaling the bilinear form so holds for all forms.)

![table_2](table_2)

Table 2. Comparing the different normalizations of bilinear forms on a simple Lie algebra. In this table, $\lambda=-6 / h^{\vee}$ is the parameter of the Classical Exceptional Series, $\theta$ is the highest root, $L_{\mu}$ is the eigenvalue of the ladder operator, and $W$ is any subrepresentation of $\wedge^{2} \mathfrak{g}$ perpendicular to $\mathfrak{g}$.

Proof. Since $\mathfrak{g}$ acts on the tensor product $\mathfrak{g} \otimes \mathfrak{g}$ by the Leibniz rule, i.e., by adding its action on each factor, we see that
![img-9.jpeg](img-9.jpeg)
where the minus sign comes from antisymmetry of the bracket.
Corollary 2.9. With respect to the Long form, $L_{2 \theta, L}=-2$. With respect to the Convenient form, $L_{2 \theta, C}=-12 / h^{\vee}$.

Lemma 2.10. Suppose that $W$ is any subrepresentation of $\wedge^{2} \mathfrak{g}$ which is perpendicular to $\mathfrak{g}$. Then $L_{W}=0$ (with respect to any form).

Proof. The projection onto the perpendicular complement of $\mathfrak{g}$ in $\wedge^{2} \mathfrak{g}$ is given by

$$
\frac{1}{2} \bigcap-\frac{1}{2} \times-\frac{1}{B}
$$

Acting on this by ladder operator, and using that triangles give a factor of $B / 2$, we get

$$
\frac{1}{2} \bigcap-\frac{1}{2} \bigcap-\frac{1}{2}
$$

But this expression is zero by the Jacobi identity.
We summarize the results of this section by Table 2, showing the values of the relevant quantities with respect to all four bilinear forms.

2.3. Quantum group conventions. In this subsection we fix conventions for quantum groups. The details here will only come up in choosing some conventions for certain diagram categories, and in the proof of quantum specialization in $\S 6$. This section is aimed at experts wishing to compare our conventions to those in other papers.

If $\mathfrak{g}$ is a complex semisimple Lie algebra, let $U_{s}(\mathfrak{g})$ denote the Drinfel'd-Jimbo quantum group, and let $\operatorname{Rep} U_{s}(\mathfrak{g})$ denote its ribbon category of representations. We follow the conventions from [Saw06, MPS11]. See [Saw06, p. 2] for a comprehensive summary of how his conventions line up with those in other sources. (Thus our $q$ is the same as Sawin's $q$ and Lusztig's $v$.) In particular we have variables $s$ and $q$ and the relation $s^{L}=q$ where $L$ is the smallest integer such that $L(\mu, v)_{S} \in \mathbb{Z}$ for any two weights $\mu$ and $v$. We always consider Type I finite dimensional representations. The quantum group itself and its representation theory only depend on $q$, while the braiding and the ribbon category depend on the additional choice of $s$. When talking about quantum groups we will typically use the bilinear form $(v, w)_{S}$ where short roots have squared length two. More generally, for $s$ not a root of unity, the braiding between irreps $V_{\mu}$ and $V_{v}$ depends only on $s^{L(\mu, v)_{S}}$ and so for $\mu$ in the root lattice (as usually happens for us) the braiding depends only on $q$.

Our reason for fixing these conventions is that it's compatible with all the other papers by KM and NS, as well as KM's quantum groups Mathematica package [Mor06]. Note that using the short form is somewhat inconvenient for our purposes in this paper, and will result in some slightly complicated changes of variables when we compare $\mathrm{QExc}_{R, v, w}$ to actual quantum group categories.

Since our tangles are unoriented, there's no way to distinguish positive and negative crossings in a link diagram, because an isotopy that rotates the crossing by 90 degrees will switch the two crossings. Nonetheless as a tangle with four boundary points, there are two crossings which are not isotopic rel boundary and we need to decide which of these crossings is declared positive (i.e., which acts on representations using the $R$-matrix, rather than $R^{-1}$ ). Since we compose tangles vertically, our convention is that a crossing is positive if it would be positive when oriented vertically, namely
is the positive crossing.
However, the following diagram is the positive twist written horizontally and thus is a positive power of $q$ times the cup, even though the middle of the diagram is a negative crossing when considered as a 4 -boundary point tangle:
![img-10.jpeg](img-10.jpeg)

For this reason, when we analyze the eigenvalues of a crossing acting on $\operatorname{Hom}\left(X^{\otimes 2}, X^{\otimes 2}\right)$ we will typically use the negative crossing, an operator we denote HTw.

If $s$ is not a root of unity, and $\Lambda^{\prime}$ is a sublattice of the weight lattice containing the root lattice, then the representations whose weights lie in $\Lambda^{\prime}$ form a ribbon subcategory. In particular, we can talk about the adjoint subcategory corresponding to the root lattice. This subcategory is exactly the subcategory generated under tensor product, direct sums, and direct summands by the adjoint representation. By the above discussion, the adjoint subcategory as a ribbon category depends only on $q$ and not $s$. We will abuse notation often by referring to subcategories supported on $\Lambda^{\prime}$ as quantum versions of the group for which representations supported on $\Lambda^{\prime}$ lift to representations of the group. For example, $S O(3)_{q}$ denotes the adjoint subcategory of the category of Type I finite-dimensional representations of $U_{q}\left(\mathrm{~sI}_{2}\right)$.

Finally, if we have a group of automorphisms of the Dynkin diagram, then this gives a group of braided autoequivalences of the corresponding ribbon category, and hence we can take the equivariantization [EGNO15, §2.7] by this action to get a new ribbon category. We will again abuse notation by referring to this as the quantum analogue of the corresponding semidirect product group. For example $\left(P S L(3) \rtimes \mathbb{Z} / 2 \mathbb{Z}\right)_{q}$ denotes the equivariantization of the subcategory of representations of $U_{q}\left(\mathrm{~sI}_{3}\right)$ which are supported on the root lattice by the group of Dynkin diagram automorphisms of $A_{2}$. This category deforms the category of representations of the group $\operatorname{PSL}(3) \rtimes \mathbb{Z} / 2 \mathbb{Z}$.

We use similar conventions for quantum enveloping algebras attached to simple basic Lie superalgebras with non-zero Killing form (see Remark 2.3). We follow the definitions of [Yam94, Zha02], except that we always normalize the inner product so that the short root has length two and use $q=q_{S}$. Also note that in [Yam94] their coproduct is opposite from ours. In general the quantum enveloping algebras depend not just on the Lie superalgebra but on the choice of simple roots. For a collection of conventions for simple basic Lie superalgebras see [FSS00]. Again, as in the classical case, by the quantum analogue of a Lie supergroup we will mean the appropriate equivariantization of the appropriate subcategory of representations of the quantized enveloping algebra.

In fact, the only quantum supergroup which we will need to understand in detail is $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)_{q}$. In $\S 2.5$, we will explain how this relates to $S O(3)_{q}$, and so understanding the general conventions for quantum supergroups will not be important for this paper. (Warning: in [MPS17] this category was denoted $O S p(1 \mid 2)_{q}$, but this was a poor choice of notation which is not compatible with how we denote categories attached to groups.)
2.4. Explicitly comparing conventions. It can sometimes be difficult to work out what conventions another paper is using, and thus to find the right change of variables between our conventions and their conventions. In this subsection we'll explain why other conventions occur and how to find the correct change of variables.

The main source of different $q$ conventions in the literature is that there are variables $q_{i}$ for each simple root $\mu_{i}$ where the formula for $q_{i}$ depends on the length of $\mu_{i}$. Our choice of $q$ is $q=q_{S}$ corresponding to the short roots, so that $q_{L}=q_{S}^{\Delta}=q^{\Delta}$. It is also common in other papers to pick $q_{L}$ as $q$. The former convention is natural if you use $\langle\cdot, \cdot\rangle_{S}$ as your inner product on the root space, while the latter convention is natural if you use $\langle\cdot, \cdot\rangle_{L}$. (More generally, there are $q$ variables associated to any pairing; see Remark 4.1.) Similarly, if you're studying a family like $\mathfrak{s o}(2 n+1)$, if you uniformly choose $q$ to be $q_{L}$, then $q_{n}=\sqrt{q}$ and if you then specialize to $\mathfrak{s o}(3)$ you end up with a choice of $q$ which is neither $q_{S}$ nor $q_{L}$ (which are equal because there's only one root).

In addition to the conventions for $q$, there are many slight variants one can give for the generators and relations. These typically do not change the category of representations at generic $q$ at all because they just correspond to rescaling the choices of $E_{i}$ and $F_{i}$ either by scalars or by powers of $K$ and so generate the same algebra $h$-adically. Because of this rescaling freedom it can sometimes be difficult to work out what $q$ conventions are being used: the relation $\left[E_{i}, F_{i}\right]=\left(K_{i}-K_{i}^{-1}\right) /\left(q_{i}-q_{i}^{-1}\right)$ changes under rescaling $E_{i}$ which allows you to change the denominator on the right-hand side. However, if you look at the Serre relation normalized so that the leading coefficient is one, then the coefficient of the next term is $-\left[1-a_{i j}\right]_{q_{i}}$, which does not change under rescaling of $E_{i}$ and so will tell you what conventions are being used. For example,

in [Zha92] the generators and relations for quantum $\mathfrak{s o}_{2 n+1}$ given use a non-standard normalization of the final $E_{n}$, but by looking at the Serre relations we see that $[2]_{q_{i}}=q+q^{-1}$ for $i<n$ but $[3]_{q_{n}}=q+1+q^{-1}$ so they've chosen $q=q_{i}=q_{L}$ and $q_{n}=q_{S}=q^{\frac{1}{2}}=q^{\frac{1}{2}}$, so Zhang's $q$ is our $q^{2}$.

Comparing conventions is much easier when you allow yourself to consider the $R$-matrix and the ribbon structure on the category of representations of the quantum group. The positive twist acts on $V_{\mu}$ by the scalar $q^{\left\langle\mu, \mu+2 \rho\right\rangle}$ where $\rho$ is the Weyl vector and $\langle\cdot, \cdot\rangle$ is the (dual) inner product in the choice of $q$. For $V_{\xi}$ a summand of $V_{\mu} \otimes V_{v}$, the square of the negative braiding acts on $\operatorname{Hom}\left(V_{\mu} \otimes V_{v}, V_{\xi}\right)$ by acting by the positive twist on $V_{\mu}$ and $V_{v}$ and the negative twist on $V_{\xi}$, and thus acts by the scalar

$$
q^{\langle\mu, \mu+2 \rho\rangle+\langle v, v+2 \rho\rangle-\langle\xi, \xi+2 \rho\rangle}
$$

In particular, on the summand where $\xi=\mu+v$, the square of the negative braiding acts by $q^{-2\langle\mu, v\rangle}$.
If $\mu=v$ and $\xi$ appears with multiplicity one, we can also ask which square root of the double braiding eigenvalue is the single braiding eigenvalue, and this can usually be worked out by looking at what happens as $q$ goes to 1 and determining whether $V_{\xi}$ lives in the symmetric square or the alternating square of $V_{\mu}$. One special case is that when $\xi=\mu+v=2 \mu$ : in this case by looking at the formula for the $R$-matrix acting on the tensor product of highest weight vectors, we can see that the single negative braiding acts by $q^{-\langle\mu, \mu\rangle}$ in the ordinary case, and $\pm q^{-\langle\mu, \mu\rangle}$ in the super case, where the sign is the parity of $\mu$.
2.5. Some trivalent ribbon categories. We now recall the definitions and fix conventions for some ribbon categories.
