Corollary 6.9. Suppose that $(\operatorname{Rep}(G), X, \tau)$ is a trivalent ribbon category with $\operatorname{dim} \operatorname{Rep}(G)_{4} \leq 5$. Then there are analytic functions $v(q)$ and $w(q)$ defined for $q$ on an open dense subset in the complex topology on $\mathbb{C}$ and a family of evaluation functors $\operatorname{Tri}_{\mathbb{C}} \rightarrow \mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}, v(q), w(q)} \rightarrow G_{q}$ which are given by rational functions.

Proof. By Proposition 6.8 we have a family of functors $\mathcal{F}_{q}: \operatorname{Tric}_{\mathbb{C}} \rightarrow G_{q}$ given by rational functions. By Corollary 1.20, after rescaling the self-duality to match our conventions for the bigon, outside of a finite set of points this functor factors through $\mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}, v(q), w(q)}$ for some $v(q)$ and $w(q)$. Moreover, by looking at the proof of Corollary 1.20, it's easy to verify that $v(q)$ and $w(q)$ are given by algebraic functions. Thus by choosing appropriate branch cuts in $\mathbb{C}$ each is given by an analytic function of $q$.

Proposition 6.10. Suppose that $\mathcal{F}_{q}: \operatorname{Tric}_{\mathbb{C}} \rightarrow G_{q}$ is given by rational functions, and that $\mathcal{F}_{1}$ is full and dominant. Then $\mathcal{F}_{q}$ is full and dominant for $q$ in some dense subset of $\mathbb{C}$.

Proof. For fixed $n$ the map is surjective on the $n$-box space at $q=1$ by assumption, and is thus surjective for $q$ in a Zariski open dense set, and thus a dense set in the ordinary complex topology. Therefore the functor is full on a countable intersection of dense sets, and thus by the Baire Category Theorem the functor is full on a dense set.

To see that it is dominant, we shrink the dense set to avoid all roots of unity, so that we can assume that $G_{q}$ is semisimple. Then the fusion rules for $G_{q}$ agree with those of $\operatorname{Rep}(G)$, so the image of the strand tensor generates and the functor is dominant.
6.2. Other 1-parameter classical families. In this section we introduce three families of symmetric ribbon categories, namely $\operatorname{Sym}(d+1), G 2(d)$, and $F 4(d)$. It will turn out these are related to $\mathrm{Q} \operatorname{Exc}_{R, v, w}$ with $v$ being a primitive 12 th root, a primitive 3 rd root, or a primitive 4 th root of unity, respectively, much as the classical exceptional family is related to $v=1$.

In all three cases a parallel phenomenon occurs: if $X$ is the strand, then in the additive completion $\mathbf{1} \oplus X$ admits the structure of an algebra object satisfying certain axioms, and that moreover these three families are universal for symmetric ribbon categories with such an algebra. We will see that for the Sym family $\mathbf{1} \oplus X$ is a commutative Frobenius algebra object, for the $G 2$ family $\mathbf{1} \oplus X$ is a Hurwitz algebra object, and for the $F 4$ family $\mathbf{1} \oplus X$ is a unital Jordan algebra object with a trace that moreover satisfies the cubic Cayley-Hamilton identity.
6.2.1. $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$. In this section we recall a description of Deligne's symmetric group family $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}$ [Del07] and a closely related trivalent symmetric ribbon category $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$, and the relationship between these categories and commutative Frobenius algebras. This is based on NS's diagrammatics for $S_{t}$ which are described in [KS20] and inspired by the diagrammatic description given by Harriger [Har21]. Since this topic is somewhat tangential to the main point of the paper, and are not difficult given the results already in [Har21], we will quickly state the correct theorems without proof. More details should appear eventually in an expanded version of [Har21]joint with NS. We will distinguish two slightly different variants, the special version $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}$ and the normalized version $S_{t}^{\text {norm }}$.

Definition 6.11. $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}$ is the symmetric ribbon category generated by a trivalent vertex and a one-valent vertex modulo the following relations:

![img-45.jpeg](img-45.jpeg)

Remark 6.12. When $t$ is not a positive integer, the Cauchy completion of $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}$ is a semisimple abelian category. When $t$ is a positive integer, then the quotient of the Cauchy completion of $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}$ by negligibles agrees with the representation category $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{t}\right)$. (See $\S 2.5 .5$ for the case $t=3$.) When $t$ is a positive integer there is also an "abelian envelope" of $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}$ which is a nonsemisimple abelian category [Del07, CO11, Har16]. The construction of this abelian category is much more subtle than the diagrammatic version, and we will have no need to consider it.

From the last defining relation, we see that any two trivalent trees on $n$ vertices are equal when thought of as morphisms in $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}$. Similarly, any two forests with the same connected components give the same morphism. The following sufficiency and consistency result follows.
Proposition 6.13. Partitions of $n$ give a basis of $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}(n)$. In particular $\operatorname{dim}\left(S_{t}^{\text {spec }}(n)\right)$ is given by the Bell Numbers, OEIS A000110 [OEI24].
Definition 6.14. A commutative Frobenius algebra over $k$ is a unital commutative associative algebra $A$ over $k$ with a trace $\operatorname{tr}: A \rightarrow k$ such that $\operatorname{tr}(x y)$ is a non-degenerate symmetric bilinear form. A commutative Frobenius algebra object in a symmetric ribbon category is a unital commutative associative algebra object $A$ with a trace $\operatorname{tr}: A \rightarrow \mathbf{1}$ such that $\operatorname{tr} \circ \mu$ is the evaluation of a symmetric self-duality ev on $A$.
Remark 6.15. We have started to distinguish between different units: plain 1 is the multiplicative unit in the base field $k$, bold 1 is the unit object in a monoidal category (usually $k$ as a vector space), and blackboard bold $\mathbb{1}$ is the unit in an algebra over $k$.

If $A$ is a Frobenius algebra object then $(\operatorname{id} \otimes \mu) \circ(\operatorname{coev} \otimes \mathrm{id})$ (where coev is the inverse of ev) defines a coproduct $\Lambda: A \rightarrow A \otimes A$ and Frobenius algebras are often axiomatized in terms of this coproduct instead of the trace.
Definition 6.16. A Frobenius algebra object is normalized if $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})=1$ and special if $\mu \circ \Lambda=\mathrm{id}$.
The following proposition is immediate from the above definition, and since this universal property characterizes $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}$, [Del07, Prop. 8.3] shows that it agrees with any other definition of $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}$.

Proposition 6.17. If $\mathcal{C}$ is a symmetric ribbon category, the groupoid of functors $S_{t}^{\text {spec }} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$ and natural isomorphisms is equivalent to the groupoid of special commutative Frobenius algebra objects in $\mathcal{C}$.

We also have the following slight variation on $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}$, which is equivalent as a symmetric ribbon category when $t \neq 0$ and which satisfies a similar universal property for normalized commutative Frobenius algebras.

Definition 6.18. Deligne's $S_{t}^{\text {norm }}$ is the symmetric ribbon category generated by a trivalent vertex and a one-valent vertex modulo the following relations:
![img-46.jpeg](img-46.jpeg)

Proposition 6.19. If $t \neq 0$, then $S_{t}^{\text {spec }}$ and $S_{t}^{\text {norm }}$ are equivalent as symmetric ribbon categories. For all $t$, partitions form a basis for $S_{t}^{\text {norm }}(n)$ and so the dimensions of Hom-spaces are again given by Bell numbers.

If $\mathcal{C}$ is a symmetric ribbon category, the groupoid of functors $S_{t}^{\text {norm }} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$ and natural isomorphisms is equivalent to the groupoid of normalized commutative Frobenius algebra objects in $\mathcal{C}$.

If $A$ is a Frobenius algebra object and $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1}) \neq 0$ then $(a \mapsto \operatorname{tr}(a) \cdot \mathbb{1} / \operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})): A \rightarrow A$ is a projection, and so $A \cong \mathbf{1} \oplus X$ for some sub-object $X$. The restriction of multiplication composed with projection onto $X$ gives a map $M: X \otimes X \rightarrow X$. It is easy to see that the Karoubi envelope of $S_{t}^{\text {norm }}$ with the object $X$ and the map $M$ is a trivalent category, and we can easily read off its defining generators and relations by expanding $A \cong \mathbf{1} \oplus X$ in the defining relations of $S_{t}^{\text {norm }}$.

Remark 6.20. If $A$ is an algebra object in a symmetric monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$ with a multiplication $\mu$ and some additional structures such as a unit $u: \mathbf{1} \rightarrow A$, or trace $\operatorname{tr}: A \rightarrow \mathbf{1}$, we will still write expressions "in elements" using dummy variables (as above). This notation will cause no confusion provided that each variable appears exactly once in each term. We can sum together such terms or set such sums equal to each other. For example, we can write $x \mapsto \operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1} x)$ to mean the composition $\operatorname{tr} \circ \mu \circ(u \otimes \mathrm{id}): A=k \otimes A \rightarrow k$. Or we can write the Jacobi identity for a Lie algebra object (using bracket as the algebra operation) as $[x,[y, z]]=[[x, y], z]+[y,[x, z]]$. Similarly, if $A$ is endowed with a symmetric self-duality, we will write a duality pairing $A \otimes A \rightarrow k$ using the notation $\langle x, y\rangle$.
Definition 6.21. Let $\operatorname{Sym}(d+1)$ be the symmetric trivalent ribbon category given by the following relations.
![img-47.jpeg](img-47.jpeg)

Proposition 6.22. The Cauchy completions of $S_{t}^{\text {norm }}$ and $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$ are equivalent. This equivalence sends the strand in $S_{t}^{\text {norm }}$ to the direct sum of the trivial and the strand in $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$.

Thus we can think of $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$ as a interpolated symmetric group category, but the strand in $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$ does not correspond to the permutation representation, but instead to the "standard representation", i.e., the irreducible representation corresponding to the partition $(d, 1)$, which is the permutation representation minus the trivial representation. The endomorphism algebras in this category are called the quasi-partition algebras in [DO14].

Definition 6.23. A Sym-algebra is a (non-unital) $k$-algebra $A$ with a symmetric bilinear form with a symmetric monoidal functor $\operatorname{Sym}(t) \rightarrow \mathrm{Vec}_{k}$ sending the object to $A$ and the trivalent vertex to the multiplication. Similarly an Sym-algebra object in a symmetric ribbon category $C$ is an object $A$ in together with a functor $\operatorname{Sym}(t) \rightarrow C$ sending the strand to $A$.

The consistency and sufficiency theorem for $S_{i}^{\text {norm }}$, Proposition 6.19, yields a similar consistency and sufficiency theorem for $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$. For each $m>1$ fix a trivalent tree with $m$ leaves. For each partition $\pi$ of $n$ into parts with no singletons, we have an element $v_{\pi}$ of $\operatorname{Sym}(d+1)_{n}$ given by connecting the vertices in each part by the fixed tree.

Lemma 6.24. The elements $v_{\pi}$, where $\pi$ ranges over partitions of $n$ into parts with no singletons, form a basis of $\operatorname{Sym}(t)_{n}$. In particular, $\operatorname{dim} \operatorname{Sym}(t)_{n}$ is the sequence OEIS A000296 [OEI24].

The universal property satisfied by $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$ is:
Proposition 6.25. Suppose $C$ is a Karoubi complete symmetric ribbon category with a normalized commutative Frobenius algebra object $A \cong \mathbf{1} \oplus X$ with $\operatorname{dim} X=d$. Then $C$ takes a symmetric monoidal functor from $\operatorname{Sym}(d+1)$ sending the strand to $X$ and the trivalent vertex to the restricted multiplication M. (That is, $X$ is an Sym-algebra object in C.)

Conversely, in the additive completion of $\operatorname{Sym}(d+1)$, the direct sum of the unit and the strand admits the structure of a normalized commutative Frobenius algebra.

Remark 6.26. Since all the relations defining $\operatorname{Sym}(0)$ hold in $\operatorname{Rep}\left(\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2), V_{1}^{-}\right)$, there's a quotient functor $\operatorname{Sym}(0) \rightarrow \operatorname{Rep}\left(\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2), V_{1}^{-}\right)$. Note that the 4 -box space for the former is 4 dimension, and the latter is 3-dimensional; this functor kills

$$
x+1 \quad\left(+2-\frac{2}{b} 4\right.
$$

In fact, it follows from [KOK22, §5] that the semisimplification of $\operatorname{Sym}(0)$ is $\operatorname{Rep}\left(\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2), V_{1}^{-}\right)$.
We conclude this section with a brief discussion about normalization of the bigon.
Remark 6.27. There are three reasonable normalizations for $b$ in the definition of $\operatorname{Sym}(d+1)$ : the "spherical" choice $b=\frac{d-1}{\sqrt{d+1}}$, the "special" choice $b=\frac{d-1}{d+1}$, and the "normalized" choice $b=d-1$. When $d+1 \neq 0$ the resulting categories are equivalent by changing the self-duality, but when $d+1=0$ more care should be taken.

In particular, when $d=-1$, our $\operatorname{Sym}(0)$ does not agree with Deligne's $S_{0}$. This is because Deligne's $S_{0}^{\text {spec }}$ has a special Frobenius algebra object with $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})=0$, while our $\operatorname{Sym}(0)$ is equivalent to $S_{0}^{\text {norm }}$ and thus has a normalized Frobenius algebra object with $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})=1$ but $\mu \circ \Delta=0$. In particular, in our category the permutation object breaks up as a direct sum of the standard and the trivial, whereas for Deligne's the permutation will be a nontrivial extension of the trivial and the standard. A similar story applies for $S O(3)_{q}$ at $q= \pm i$ but for (not necessarily commutative) Frobenius algebra objects in a (not necessarily symmetric) tensor category. We hope to address this further in a later paper.

# 6.2.2. Classical G2 family. 

Definition 6.28. The classical G2(d) family is the symmetric ribbon category generated by a trivalent vertex modulo the following relations:
![img-48.jpeg](img-48.jpeg)

Following the PhD thesis of Boos [Boo98] in German, and its several English language expositions [Wes10, Str19, Bae01], the classical G2 family is closely related to Hurwitz algebras. We summarize this as follows.

Definition 6.29. A vector product algebra is a (non-unital) $k$-algebra $A$ with a symmetric bilinear form with a symmetric monoidal functor $G 2(d) \rightarrow \mathrm{Vec}_{k}$ sending the object to $A$ and the trivalent vertex to the multiplication. We will also call it a G2-algebra. Similarly we will refer to an object $A$ in a symmetric ribbon category $\mathcal{C}$ together with a functor $G 2(d) \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$ as a G2-algebra object in $\mathcal{C}$.

Example 6.30. $\mathbb{R}^{3}$ with the standard bilinear form and multiplication given by the cross product is a vector product algebra (or G2-algebra) over $\mathbb{R}$. For this example $d=3$. If we endow $\mathbb{R}^{3}$ with the defining action of $S O(3)$ then the standard bilinear form and the cross product are $S O(3)$ equivariant. Thus the defining representation of $S O(3)$ is a G2-algebra object in $\operatorname{Rep}(S O(3))$.

Definition 6.31. A Hurwitz algebra over $k$ is a unital (not necessarily associative) algebra $A$ over $k$ with a non-degenerate symmetric bilinear form $\langle\cdot, \cdot\rangle: A \otimes A \rightarrow k$ such that the norm map $N(v):=\langle v, v\rangle$ satisfies $N(\mathbb{1})=1$ and $N(u v)=N(u) N(v)$.

Hurwitz algebras are also called unital composition algebras. Often you will see composition algebras and Hurwitz algebras defined directly using a quadratic norm map $N$ in the definition instead of a bilinear form, but this is not necessary outside of characteristic 2.

In any Hurwitz algebra we can define an involution $\tilde{\cdot}$ via $\tilde{v}=2\langle v, \mathbb{1}\rangle-v$, and it follows that $N(v) \mathbb{1}=\widetilde{v} v$.

Example 6.32. The real numbers, complex numbers, quaternions, and octonions, with their standard norms, are Hurwitz algebras over $\mathbb{R}$. Moreover, in these examples the bilinear form is positive definite, from which it follows that they're all division algebras with the inverse of $x$ given by $\bar{x} / N(x)$. Their complexifications $\left(\mathbb{C}, \mathbb{C} \oplus \mathbb{C}, M_{2}(\mathbb{C})\right.$, and the bi-octonions) are Hurwitz algebras over $\mathbb{C}$. (Since the quadratic form is no longer definite, they are not division algebras.)

We would like to give a definition of Hurwitz algebra objects in symmetric ribbon categories, but there's a difficulty in generalizing directly, since the construction of $N$ implicitly uses a diagonal map. In order to remedy this situation we take the "polarization" of the identity $N(u v)=$ $N(u) N(v)$ as follows. Substitute $u=a+b$ and $v=c+d$ and then take the terms that are homogeneous of degree $(1,1,1,1)$, yielding (after dividing by 2 ):

$$
\langle a c, b d\rangle+\langle a d, b c\rangle=2\langle a, b\rangle\langle c, d\rangle
$$

Conversely Equation (26) implies the usual composition identity $N(u v)=N(u) N(v)$ by setting $a=b=u$ and $c=d=v$ and dividing by 2 .

Definition 6.33. If $C$ is a symmetric ribbon category, then a Hurwitz algebra object in $C$ is an object $A$ which is symmetrically self-dual, endowed with a multiplication $\mu: A \otimes A \rightarrow A$ and a unit $u: \mathbf{1} \rightarrow A$, satisfying the unit axioms, and such that $\langle\mathbb{1}, \mathbb{1}\rangle=1$ and $\langle a c, b d\rangle+\langle a d, b c\rangle=2\langle a, b\rangle\langle c, d\rangle$.

In this definition we have used the convention from Remark 6.20 to interpret these algebraic expressions as morphisms in $C$. We could also express these identities using diagram notation as follows:
![img-49.jpeg](img-49.jpeg)

Warning 6.34. The multiplication map on a Hurwitz algebra is typically not rotationally invariant (i.e., the inner product is typically not associative).

Remark 6.35. We could treat vector product algebras in a similar way, and get the axioms in Definition 6.29 from polarizing the natural identities for the cross product and dot product, namely $\langle x, x y\rangle=0=\langle x y, y\rangle$ and $\langle x y, x y\rangle=\langle x, x\rangle\langle y, y\rangle-\langle x, y\rangle^{2}$ [Wik22].

If $A$ is a Hurwitz algebra object, then we have a trace map which is dual to the unit map. Moreover, the first axiom of a Hurwitz algebra object tells you that $\operatorname{tr}(\cdot) \mathbb{1}: A \rightarrow A$ is an idempotent, and so in the idempotent completion of $C$, we have $A \cong \mathbf{1} \oplus X$ for some sub-object $X$. The restriction of multiplication composed with projection onto $X$ gives a map $M: X \otimes X \rightarrow X$.

Proposition 6.36 ([Str19, Thm. 25]). Suppose $C$ is an idempotent complete symmetric ribbon category with a Hurwitz algebra object $A \cong \mathbf{1} \oplus X$ and $\operatorname{dim} X=d$. Then $C$ takes a symmetric monoidal functor from $G 2(d)$ sending the strand to $X$ and the trivalent vertex to the restricted multiplication $M$ (i.e., $X$ is a G2-algebra object in C).

Conversely, in the additive completion of $G 2(d)$, the direct sum of the unit and the strand admits a unique structure of a Hurwitz algebra such that its traceless part agrees with the G2(d)-algebra structure on $X$.

Remark 6.37. Explicitly, the multiplication on the Hurwitz algebra $1 \oplus X$ is given by $(a, x)(b, y)=$ $(a b-\langle x, y\rangle, a y+b x+x y)$. In particular, the component of the multiplication map in $X \otimes X \rightarrow \mathbf{1}$ is not the pairing $X \otimes X \rightarrow \mathbf{1}$ induced by the symmetric self-duality of $A$, but instead those two maps are negatives of each other. One good way to think about this is that $\langle x, y\rangle=\operatorname{tr}(x \bar{y})$ and so they're negatives of each other when restricted to $X$, since $\bar{x}=-x$ in $X$. In general, there are some parameters involved in turning a non-unital algebra $X$ into a unital algebra $1 \oplus X$; see the proof of Proposition 6.51.

The following lemma proves sufficiency for the classical G2 family.
Lemma 6.38. The Hom spaces for G2(d) are spanned by planar non-elliptic diagrams and thus are bounded by the dimensions of the Hom spaces for the category of representations of $G_{2}$.

Proof. First, use the last (defining) identity to remove any crossings to reduce to planar diagrams. By [Wes10, Eq. 15], these relations imply a relation simplifying the square into a sum of planar terms with no faces, and by the same argument as [Wes10, §3.1] the pentagon also simplifies into

a sum of planar terms with no faces. Thus, by Euler characteristic (see [Kup96, §4]) every Hom space is spanned by the non-elliptic diagrams.

The following propositions show that consistency at generic values of the parameter is false, and show specialization at the points that are consistent; together they give a generalization of the classification of Hurwitz algebras due to Hurwitz.
Proposition 6.39 ([Wes10]). G2(d) is the zero category unless $d=0,1,3$, or 7 .
If $A$ is one of the four real Hurwitz algebras from Example 6.32, then let $G_{A}$ denote the group of unital algebra automorphisms of the real Hurwitz algebra $A$ which preserve the bilinear form, as in $\S 6.1$. (It's not difficult to see that these groups can also be described as the groups of automorphisms of the corresponding real vector product algebra $X$ which preserve the bilinear form.) Since the inner product on the real Hurwitz algebras are positive definite, it follows that $G_{A}$ is a compact group, and that its category of complex representations has a unitary structure. The groups $G_{A}$ are trivial, $S_{2}, S O(3)$, and the compact form of $G_{2}$, respectively, as shown in Table 9 on page 87 .
Proposition 6.40. If $d=0,1,3$, or 7 , take $A$ to be $\mathbb{R}, \mathbb{C}, \mathbb{H}$, or $\mathbb{O}$, respectively and define $G_{A}$ as above. Then at these four values of $d$, the category $G 2(d)$ has a full and dominant functor to the category $\operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{A}\right)$.
Proof. Since $A$ is a real Hurwitz algebra of dimension $d+1$ we have a functor $\mathcal{F}: G 2(d) \rightarrow$ $\operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{A}\right)$.

This functor is full and dominant by Proposition 6.5 and Remark 6.6.
Note that when $A=\mathbb{R}$ the image of the strand in $G 2(0)$ is the zero object in $\operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{A}\right)$ and when $A=\mathbb{C}$ the image of the trivalent vertex in $G 2(1)$ is the zero map. (The map $M$ defined above is zero.) So in both of these cases the target category is not trivalent.

# 6.2.3. Classical F4 family. 

Definition 6.41. The classical $F 4(d)$ family, studied earlier by DPT [Thu05], is the symmetric ribbon category generated by a trivalent vertex modulo the following relations:
![img-50.jpeg](img-50.jpeg)

We have used a different bigon normalization than the one used in [Thu05], for reasons that will become apparent below.

As in the case of the classical exceptional family, we can change variables $v=(d+4) / 6$ to get a somewhat better behaved parameter, following [DG02]. For our purposes an even better parameterization is by $\eta=(d-2) / 12=(v-1) / 2$. (This is not the same as the $\eta$ parameter in [Thu05].)

We have the following sufficiency conjecture, with some partial evidence given in [Thu05].
Conjecture 6.42. F4(d) has finite dimensional Hom spaces.

As with the G2 family, consistency fails.
Proposition 6.43 ([Thu05]). F4(d) is the zero category unless $d \in\{-2,-1,0,2,5,8,14,26\}$.
Our remaining goal is to prove a version of specialization at most of these values.
Definition 6.44. An F4-algebra is a (non-unital) $k$-algebra $X$ with a symmetric bilinear form with a symmetric monoidal functor $F 4(d) \rightarrow \mathrm{Vec}_{k}$ sending the object to $X$ and the trivalent vertex to the multiplication. Similarly we will refer to an object $X$ in a symmetric ribbon category $C$ together with a functor $F 4(d) \rightarrow C$ as an $F 4$-algebra object in $C$.

In the last section we saw that G2-algebras appear exactly as the kernel of the trace $x \mapsto\langle x, \mathbb{1}\rangle$ on a Hurwitz algebra $A$. We will give a similar characterization here of $F 4$-algebras as the traceless part of cubic tracial Jordan algebras, following [Cvi08, Cvi77, GSZ23].

Definition 6.45. A Jordan algebra over $k$ is a commutative (non-associative) $k$-algebra $A$ satisfying the Jordan identity

$$
(x y)(x x)=x(y(x x))
$$

A tracial Jordan algebra is a Jordan algebra together with a unit $k \rightarrow A$ satisfying the usual unit axioms, and a non-degenerate symmetric bilinear form $\langle\cdot, \cdot\rangle: A \otimes A \rightarrow k$ which is associative, $\langle x, y z\rangle=\langle x y, z\rangle$, and satisfies $\langle\mathbb{1}, \mathbb{1}\rangle=1$. In a tracial Jordan algebra we let $\operatorname{tr}(x):=\langle x, \mathbb{1}\rangle$. Associativity guarantees that $\langle x, y\rangle=\operatorname{tr}(x y)$ and $\operatorname{tr}((x y) z)=\operatorname{tr}(x(y z))$.

Since $\langle x, y\rangle=\operatorname{tr}(x y)$ we will often specify a tracial Jordan algebra by specifying the trace instead of the bilinear form; of course one then needs to check that the resulting bilinear form is non-degenerate. The assumption that $\langle\mathbb{1}, \mathbb{1}\rangle=1=\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})$ is not essential, we could instead assume only that $\langle\mathbb{1}, \mathbb{1}\rangle \neq 0$. But this normalization is convenient and one can always rescale the bilinear form to ensure it. However there are a few places where our normalization assumption appears unexpectedly, see Remark 6.50.

Diagrammatically we will denote $A$ by an unoriented strand (since the bilinear form gives it the structure of a symmetrically self-dual vector space), the unit by a bullet, and the multiplication by trivalent vertex (which is allowed since it is rotationally invariant by associativity of the trace).

Example 6.46. If $A$ is an associative algebra, then $x \circ y:=\frac{x y+y x}{2}$ makes $A$ into a unital Jordan algebra. If $A=M_{n}(k)$ then together with the normalized trace this turns $A$ into a tracial Jordan algebra.

As before, Definition 6.45 is not amenable to generalization to algebra objects in a ribbon category due to the repeated arguments in the Jordan identity. Again, we polarize by substituting $x=a+b+c$ and looking at the terms that are homogeneous of degree $(1,1,1)$. As before, in characteristic 0 this polarized identity is equivalent to the usual Jordan identity. Each side of the Jordan identity contributes a sum over permutations of three letters.

Definition 6.47. A tracial Jordan algebra object in a symmetric ribbon category is a unital algebra object $A$ together with a choice of symmetric self-duality and a rotationally invariant map $A \otimes A \rightarrow$

$A$ which satisfies the Jordan algebra axiom
![img-51.jpeg](img-51.jpeg)
(where Sym and $\wedge$ denote the symmetrizer and anti-symmetrizer, and we've labelled strands by $a, b, c, y$ to allow easy comparison with the Jordan axiom; the unlabelled strand is the output value) and trace axiom

$$
\square \quad=1
$$

Remark 6.48. If you compose with the unit (or trace) on any of the five outer strings of Eq. (28), then it's easy to check that the resulting identity automatically holds.

Since $\operatorname{tr}(\cdot) \mathbb{1}: A \rightarrow A$ is an idempotent, we have that $A=\mathbf{1} \oplus X$ for some object $X$ in the idempotent completion of $\mathcal{C}$. Moreover $X$ inherits a multiplication structure $M(x, y)=x y-$ $\operatorname{tr}(x y) \mathbb{1}: X \otimes X \rightarrow X$ and a symmetric self-duality.

Definition 6.49. A traceless Jordan algebra object in a symmetric ribbon category is a symmetrically self-dual object $X$ with a rotationally invariant multiplication $M: X \otimes X \rightarrow X$ satisfying the identity
![img-52.jpeg](img-52.jpeg)

Remark 6.50. The coefficient in the traceless Jordan algebra axiom (29) implicitly depends on our normalization $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})=1$, because the formula for the projection onto $X$ depends on that normalization. A non-polarized version of Eq. (29) is

$$
(x y)(x x)+\langle x, y\rangle x x=x(y(x x))+x\langle y, x x\rangle
$$

Note that $X$ retains an associative normalized duality pairing $X \otimes X \rightarrow \mathbf{1}$, but does not have a trace since there's no unit in $X$.

Proposition 6.51. The traceless part of a tracial Jordan algebra object $A$ is a traceless Jordan algebra object $X$. Conversely, if $X$ is a traceless Jordan algebra then there exists a unique tracial Jordan algebra structure on $\mathbf{1} \oplus X$ whose traceless part is $X$.

Proof. For the first part, rewrite the identity on $A$ as a sum of projections onto $\mathbf{1}$ and $X$, and then take the component of (28) where you choose the projection onto $X$ at every boundary point. This results in a sum over all ways of deleting or not deleting each interior edge. Only two terms survive, giving (29).

In the converse direction, first check uniqueness: we show that $A=\mathbf{1} \oplus X$ must have trace $\operatorname{tr}(a, x)=a$ and multiplication

$$
(a, x) \cdot{ }_{A}(b, y)=(a b+\langle x, y\rangle, a y+b x+x y)
$$

The formula for the trace follows from the normalization of the trace and that $X$ is supposed to be the traceless part of $X$. In order to get the formula for multiplication we look componentwise. Unitality and the fact that the multiplication on $X$ is inherited from the multiplication on $A$ determines multiplication on every component except for the $X \otimes X \rightarrow \mathbf{1}$ component. Looking at the inner products, we see

$$
\langle x, y\rangle_{X}=\langle(0, x),(0, y)\rangle_{A}=\operatorname{tr}\left((0, x) \cdot{ }_{A}(0, y)\right)
$$

and hence the component $X \otimes X \rightarrow \mathbf{1}$ must be given by $\langle x, y\rangle$.
Now we need to check that $A$ with the above multiplication and trace is a tracial Jordan algebra. Non-degeneracy of the bilinear form and normalization of the trace are easy. We check the Jordan axiom in components, i.e., for each of the four legs we have to pick either 1 or $X$ and then check that the relation holds on that component. This is automatic, essentially by Remark 6.48, but is also easy to check directly. For example, if one of the inputs at the bottom is $\mathbf{1}$ and all the others are $X$ then we need to check that the following expression in $X$ vanishes:
![img-53.jpeg](img-53.jpeg)

This follows immediately from symmetry considerations.
The relevance of Jordan algebras to the $F 4$ family is explained by the following lemma.
Lemma 6.52 ([Cvi77, Eqn. 15.15]). An F4(d) algebra object is a traceless Jordan algebra object.
Proof. Apply the $F 4(d)$ relation (27) to the lower internal edge in Eq. (29) and combine terms which differ by applying a crossing to the symmetrizer to yield
![img-54.jpeg](img-54.jpeg)

The first term in this sum vanishes because it equal to its own negative by applying a full twist at the top and the bottom of the diagram. By easier symmetries, the second term is zero and the third and fourth terms cancel, so we get 0 as desired.

The Jordan algebras related to the $F 4$ family satisfy an additional identity, which is the CayleyHamilton identity satisfied by 3-by-3 matrices. Note that Jordan algebras are power associative, so $x^{3}$ is unambiguous.

Definition 6.53. A tracial Jordan algebra is cubic Cayley-Hamilton if, for all $x$,

$$
x^{3}-3 \operatorname{tr}(x) x^{2}+\left(\frac{9}{2} \operatorname{tr}(x)^{2}-\frac{3}{2} \operatorname{tr}\left(x^{2}\right)\right) x-\left(\frac{9}{2} \operatorname{tr}(x)^{3}-\frac{9}{2} \operatorname{tr}(x) \operatorname{tr}\left(x^{2}\right)+\operatorname{tr}\left(x^{3}\right)\right) \mathbb{1}=0
$$

A traceless Jordan algebra is cubic Cayley-Hamilton if it satisfies the identity

$$
a^{3}=\frac{1}{2}\langle a, a\rangle a
$$

Remark 6.54. The coefficients in the cubic Cayley-Hamilton relation depend on our choice of normalization. That is, if $M$ is a 3 -by-3 matrix with the normalized trace, then the sum of the eigenvalues of $M$ is $3 \operatorname{tr}(M)$. The coefficients would be nicer if we had normalized so that $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})=3$ so that it agreed with the matrix trace for 3-by-3 matrices.

Note that if you don't make assumptions about the normalization of the trace then Eq. (30) on its own does restrict the allowed normalizations. Eq. (30) forces $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})$ to be one of $1,2 / 3$, or $1 / 3$, but although there are examples where each of the three traces appears, this identity is only related to the Cayley-Hamilton theorem if we additionally assume $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})=1$.

Example 6.55. If $R$ is a Hurwitz algebra, $M_{3}(R)$ with its standard tracial Jordan algebra structure is cubic Cayley-Hamilton. If $R$ is a Hurwitz algebra, let $H_{3}(R)$ denote the Hermitian 3-by-3 matrices over $R$. (Here Hermitian means equal to its conjugate transpose, where conjugate is the conjugate in the sense of Hurwitz algebras.) This is a Jordan subalgebra of $M_{3}(R)$ and thus also cubic CayleyHamilton. The significance of $H_{3}(R)$ is that, if the inner product on $R$ is positive-definite (as for $R=\mathbb{R}, \mathbb{C}, \mathbb{H}, \mathbb{O})$, then the inner product on $H_{3}(R)$ is the Frobenius inner product and thus also positive-definite.

Example 6.56. Suppose that $\left(c_{1}, c_{2}, \ldots c_{n}\right)$ are non-zero numbers summing to 1 . Then $\mathbb{R}^{n}$ with component-wise multiplication and

$$
\operatorname{tr}\left(a_{1}, \ldots, a_{n}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{n} c_{i} a_{i}
$$

is a tracial Jordan algebra.
For $n=3$ and trace given by $(1 / 3,1 / 3,1 / 3)$ we have that $\mathbb{R}^{3}$ satisfies cubic Cayley-Hamilton, because it is a diagonal subalgebra of $M_{3}(\mathbb{R})$. Note that the proper summands do not satisfy $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})=1$ but do satisfy the Jordan algebra (28) and cubic Cayley-Hamilton (30) axioms. These give examples of the phenomenon mentioned in Remark 6.54. For $n=2$ and trace given by $(2 / 3,1 / 3)$ we have that $\mathbb{R}^{2}$ satisfies Eq. (30) because it is the diagonal subalgebra of $M_{3}(\mathbb{R})$ where we repeat the first entry. Finally, for $n=1$ and trace given by (1) we again have a cubic CayleyHamilton Jordan algebra.

As usual to move from algebras to algebra objects we need to polarize the cubic CayleyHamilton identities.

Definition 6.57. A tracial Jordan algebra object is cubic Cayley-Hamilton if it satisfies
![img-55.jpeg](img-55.jpeg)

A traceless Jordan algebra object is cubic Cayley-Hamilton if it satisfies

$$
\square+\square+\square=\frac{1}{2}\left(\square+\square+\square \square\right)
$$

As in Remark 6.48, if you compose with the unit (or trace) on any of the four outer strings of (31), then it's easy to check that the resulting identity automatically holds. Thus the traceless part of the identity is the only interesting part.

Lemma 6.58. If $A$ is a cubic Cayley-Hamilton tracial Jordan algebra object then its traceless part $X$ is cubic Cayley-Hamilton. Conversely, if $X$ is a cubic Cayley-Hamilton traceless Jordan algebra object, then the unique Jordan algebra structure on $1 \oplus X$ is cubic Cayley-Hamilton.

Proof. The forward direction follows quickly from looking at the $X \otimes X \otimes X \rightarrow X$ component of the tracial cubic Cayley-Hamilton identity. Only the first and fourth terms of the identity survive, but the first term contributes a sum of two terms:
![img-56.jpeg](img-56.jpeg)

Now expand the symmetrizer.
In the backwards direction the same calculation run backwards shows that the tracial cubic Cayley-Hamilton axiom holds on the $X \otimes X \otimes X \rightarrow X$ component. We need to also check the other components. This is a tedious but straightforward check: for example, if one of the inputs is $\mathbf{1}$ and the others are $X$ then only the first two terms of the Cayley-Hamilton identity contribute. For the first term, each permutation contributes a trivalent vertex, while for the second term all but two permutations vanish and the remaining two contribute a trivalent vertex. Thus we get $6-3 \cdot 2=0$ copies of the trivalent vertex. The other calculations are similar.

Note that the polarized cubic Cayley-Hamilton identity in the traceless case is exactly the key relation in defining the $F 4$ family! In particular the following Lemma follows.

Lemma 6.59. $X$ is an F4-algebra object in $\mathcal{C}$ if and only if $X$ is a cubic Cayley-Hamilton traceless Jordan algebra object such that the lollipop vanishes.

Proof. Given an $F 4$-algebra object $X$, the traceless cubic Cayley-Hamilton and vanishing lollipop are immediate, and $X$ is a traceless Jordan algebra object by Lemma 6.52. For the other direction,

we have an object $X$ satisfying
![img-57.jpeg](img-57.jpeg)
and we need to compute the values of the bigon and the triangle. Attaching a cap to the bottom of the main relation and dividing by 2 yields the bigon value, while attaching a trivalent vertex to the bottom, using the value of the bigon, and solving for the triangle, yields the triangle value.

We next note that there is a one-parameter family of cubic Cayley-Hamilton traceless Jordan algebra objects where the lollipop is non-zero. We anticipate that this is the only such example, but since the proof is not short we will not attempt it here.

Example 6.60. Let $\mathcal{S} \mathcal{M}_{d}$ be the symmetric ribbon category generated by a rotationally invariant 3 -valent vertex and a 1-valent vertex modulo the following relations:
![img-58.jpeg](img-58.jpeg)

The strand in $\mathcal{S} \mathcal{M}_{d}$ with the trivalent vertex as multiplication is a cubic Cayley-Hamilton traceless Jordan algebra. Moreover, if $d \neq 2$, we have

$$
\square=\frac{2-d}{2} \uparrow \neq 0
$$

Since the trivalent vertex can be simplified, this category is generated by just the 1-valent vertex. Moreover, as usual, we have a projection $\frac{1}{2} \operatorname{tr}(\cdot) \mathbb{1}: X \rightarrow X$ so in the Karoubi envelope $X \cong \mathbf{1} \oplus Y$. Conversely, if $Y$ is any self-dual object in a symmetric ribbon category then in the additive envelope $\mathbf{1} \oplus Y$ we can define a cubic Cayley-Hamilton traceless Jordan algebra by the above formula. The corresponding tracial Jordan algebra is a direct sum of Jordan algebras $\mathbf{1} \oplus(\mathbf{1} \oplus Y)$ where the first factor has the trivial Jordan algebra structure but with $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})=\frac{1}{3}$ and the second factor is a "spin factor" Jordan algebra where $(a, v)(b, w)=\left(a b+\frac{3}{2}\langle v, w\rangle, a w+b v\right)$ and $\operatorname{tr}(a, v)=\frac{2}{3} a$. Note that the individual factors are not cubic Cayley-Hamilton: they satisfy the defining identity, but have $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})=1 / 3$ and $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})=2 / 3$ respectively (instead of $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbb{1})=1$ as we have required).

In the specialization result, in addition to the examples of Jordan algebras given above, we will also use two Jordan superalgebras.

Example 6.61. In characteristic not 2,3 , or 5 there are exactly two simple cubic Cayley-Hamilton tracial Jordan superalgebras (i.e., tracial Jordan algebra objects in the category of super vector spaces) which are not purely even [BE03, Prop. 5.1] (see [Eld11, Prop. 3.2] for a correction in characteristic 5 due to McCrimmon). The first is the (1|2) dimensional algebra $J^{0 \mid 2}$ with basis $\mathbb{1}, x, y$ with $(a x+b y)(c x+d y)=\operatorname{det}\left(\begin{array}{ll}a & b \\ c & d\end{array}\right)$. The second is the (2|2)-dimensional algebra $D_{2}$ spanned by even elements $e$ and $f$ satisfying $e^{2}=e, f^{2}=f, e f=0$ and $\mathbb{1}=e+f$, and two odd

elements $x$ and $y$ satisfying $e x=\frac{1}{2} x=f x, e y=\frac{1}{2} y=f y, x y=e+2 f=\mathbb{1}+f$ and with $\operatorname{tr}(e)=\frac{2}{3}$, $\operatorname{tr}(f)=\frac{1}{3}$, and $\operatorname{tr}(x)=\operatorname{tr}(y)=0$.

If $A$ is real cubic Cayley-Hamilton tracial Jordan algebra with positive definite bilinear form, then let $G_{A}$ denote the group of unital algebra automorphisms of $A$ which preserve the bilinear form. (It's not difficult to see that these groups can also be described as the groups of automorphisms of the corresponding traceless Jordan algebra.) Since it preserves a positive definite form, $G_{A}$ is compact and the category $\operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{A}\right)$ has a $C^{*}$-structure. One can similarly define a supergroup $G_{A}$ of automorphisms of a tracial Jordan superalgebra, though we do not specify the notion of compactness there.

If $d=-2,-1,0,2,5,8,14,26$, take $A_{d}$ to be the respective following $d+1$ dimensional real cubic Cayley-Hamilton tracial Jordan (super)-algebras from Examples 6.61, 6.56, and 6.55: $J^{0 \mid 2}, D_{2}, \mathbb{R}$, $\mathbb{R}^{3}, H_{3}(\mathbb{R}), H_{3}(\mathbb{C}), H_{3}(\mathbb{H}), H_{3}(\mathbb{O})$.

Proposition 6.62. For $d=-2,-1,0,2,5,8,14,26$, the (super)-group $G_{A_{d}}$ is, respectively, $(S L(2), \varepsilon=$ $-1),\left(\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2), \varepsilon_{A}\right)$, trivial, $S_{3}, S O(3), P U(3) \rtimes \mathbb{Z} / 2 \mathbb{Z}, P U S p(3)$, and $F_{4}$.

These groups are also listed in Table 8 on page 85. In the cases when $A_{d}$ is a super-algebra, we are looking at a category of super-representations as explained in $\S 2.5 .2$. Here $U S p(3)$ means the compact form of $C_{3}$ (i.e., the unitary quaternion group), and likewise for $F_{4}$ we take the compact form.

Proof. For $d=0,2$, the result follows immediately by inspection of the algebra. For $d=-2$, by inspection we see that the automorphisms of $J^{0 \mid 2}$ are $S L(2)$; this representation $V_{(1)}$ should be viewed as odd, and the tensor category this generates is $\operatorname{Rep}(S L(2), \varepsilon=-1)$. For $d=-1$, by [BE03, Lemma 2.4] we see that the Lie superalgebra of derivations of $D_{2}$ is $\mathfrak{\operatorname { s p }}(1 \mid 2)$, with traceless part the representation $V_{1}^{\sim}$. From the analysis in $\S 2.5 .2$, it follows that the Lie supergroup is $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$.

The remaining cases are automorphisms of $H_{3}(R)$ for $R$ a Hurwitz algebra, which are described by Orlitzky [Orl23].

Proposition 6.63. If $d=0,2,5,8,14,26$, then $F 4(d)$ has a full and dominant functor to the category $\operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{A_{d}}\right)$.

Proof. For $d \neq 2$, the lollipop is zero since the traceless part of $A$ is a non-trivial simple $G_{A^{-}}$ module. A direct calculation for $d=2$ shows the lollipop is zero in that case too. Since $A$ is a cubic Cayley-Hamilton tracial Jordan algebra of dimension $d+1$ with lollipop zero, we have a functor $\mathcal{F}: F 4(d) \rightarrow \operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{A_{d}}\right)$. This functor is full and dominant by Proposition 6.5 and Remark 6.6.

We expect that Proposition 6.63 also holds at $d=-2,-1$, but there are some technical issues in the supergroup case, since we need both the appropriate version of Tannaka-Krein duality and the right analogue of compactness; these are both used in Proposition 6.5. Note also that for $d=-2$ the quantization of this functor will be given by rational functions in $s=q^{1 / 2}$ rather than rational functions in $q$.

Remark 6.64. The series of Lie algebras on the last four lines of Table 8 is well-known, particularly the construction of $F_{4}$ as $H_{3}(\mathbb{O})$. There are descriptions of the other automorphism groups going back to Kalisch [Kal47, Thm. 6] (for $H_{3}(\mathbb{R})$ and $\left.H_{3}(\mathbb{H})\right)$ and Jacobson [Jac59] (in very large generality), but the fact that $\operatorname{Aut}\left(H_{3}(\mathbb{C})\right)$ is not connected seems to be relatively little-noticed in the literature. The series appears prominently in the work of Freudenthal [Fre64] and Tits [Tit66] as part of their work on the magic square, and has seen many other developments and explanations

since then. However, almost all references only consider the square as Lie algebras and not the specific Lie groups necessary to get the correct representation theory. This is perhaps because the natural version of the magic square as Lie groups is not symmetric, as seen in the work of Deligne and Gross [DG02], who give an extended magic triangle, agreeing with the groups in Table 7 on the E8 row, Table 8 on the F4 row, and Table 9 on the G2 row. (The E6 and E7 rows in Deligne-Gross do not give trivalent categories in our sense.)

Deligne-Gross make assertions about uniformity of the representation theory on each of their rows, but do not prove it for the $F 4$ row. Most of our work on this paper came before the recent developments [GSZ23, Mou22, SW22], but the results and ideas here in $\S 6.2 .3$ are strongly influenced by reading [GSZ23].

Remark 6.65. In [GSZ23] they find an additional pentagon relation in the kernel of the map $F 4(26) \rightarrow \operatorname{Rep}\left(F_{4}\right)$, using the fact that $\operatorname{dim} \mathcal{B}_{5}=15$ for $\left(F_{4}, V_{(0,0,0,1)}\right)$. For the $\mathfrak{c}_{3}, \mathfrak{a}_{2}$, and $\mathfrak{a}_{1}$ lines in the $F 4$ family, the computations in $\S 5.2$ show that the 5 -box space is at least 16 -dimensional, and so there is no reason to believe this pentagon relation holds; as a result, we do not use it in our definition of $F 4(d)$.

- $v=e^{5 \cdot 2 \pi i / 12}$ with $\alpha=\frac{i b}{2}$.

The eigenvalues of the negative crossing on the 4 -box space are $(1,1,-1)$.
Lemma 6.68. The golden categories are quotients of $S O(3)_{q}$ at $q$ a fifth or tenth root of unity. The three relations for $S O(3)_{q}$ given above correspond to $v=q^{2}$, to $v=q^{2} \omega$, or to $v=q^{2} \omega^{2}$ for a primitive cube root $\omega$. In addition, for the golden categories, there's a 2-dimensional space of relations with $v=q^{2}$, i.e., there's such a relation for every $\alpha$ including 0 and $\infty$. The eigenvalues of the negative crossing on the 4 -box space are $\left(q^{4},-q^{2}\right)$.

Proof. Plug the golden category formula for $\square$ into the $S O(3)_{q}$ braiding relation to get a formula for the crossing in terms of the Temperley-Lieb diagrams. This gives a relation with $\alpha=\infty$ and $v=q^{2}$. Linear combinations of this relation with the $v=q^{2}$ relation from the previous lemma gives relations with $v=q^{2}$ and $\alpha$ arbitrary.

The eigenvectors are just the cupcap diagram and $\square$ (i.e., the projections onto the trivial and standard objects), so they are just the twist factors $\left(-q^{2}, q^{4}\right)$.

Lemma 6.69. $\left(G_{2}, V_{(1,0)}\right)_{q}$ satisfies two instances of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ), namely $\alpha=-\frac{b}{q_{3}(q) \varphi_{6}(q)}\left(\omega^{2} q-\omega q^{-1}\right)$ and $v=\omega q$ for $\omega$ a primitive cube root of unity. This $\alpha$ corresponds to $w= \pm q^{-1}= \pm \omega v^{-1}$ or $w=$ $\pm \omega q^{2}= \pm \omega^{2} v^{2}$. The eigenvalues of the negative crossing on the 4 -box space are $\left(-q^{6}, q^{12}, q^{-2},-1\right)$.

Lemma 6.70. $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$ satisfies two instances of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ), namely

- $v=e^{2 \pi i / 12}$ with $\alpha=\frac{i b}{2}$;
- $v=e^{5 \cdot 2 \pi i / 12}$ with $\alpha=\frac{i b}{2}$.
(Recall this is singular for the change of variables.) The eigenvalues of the negative crossing on the 4 -box space are $(1,1,-1,1)$.

When $t=0$ the relations for $\operatorname{Sym}(0)$ includes two of the three relations that $\left(\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2), V_{1}^{-}\right)$ satisfies in Lemma 6.67. See Remark 6.26.

Lemma 6.71. $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$ satisfies three instances of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ), namely

- $v=e^{2 \pi i / 12}$ with $\alpha=-i b$;
- $v=e^{5 \cdot 2 \pi i / 12}$ with $\alpha=-i b$; and
- $v=i$ with $\alpha=-\frac{i}{2} b$.

The eigenvalues of the negative crossing on the 4 -box space are $(1,1,-1)$.
6.4. 4-dimensional 4-box space. In this section we give a partial classification of trivalent ribbon categories with $\operatorname{dim} C(4) \leq 4$, extending $\S 2.6$. We will need this in our results about roots of unity.

Lemma 6.72. If $\mathcal{C}$ is a trivalent ribbon category then either $\mathcal{C}$ is one of the Golden Categories or the following three diagrams are linearly independent:
![img-59.jpeg](img-59.jpeg)
(Compare to Lemma 3.5, which had a crossing in place of the last diagram.)

Proof. If there is a linear relation between these diagrams with zero coefficient on the third diagram, then composing on the top or right with a trivalent vertex shows the trivalent vertex is zero, which is a contradiction. So WLOG we have a relation of the form

$$
x=x \quad \square
$$

Attaching a cap on the top and on the right yields $0=x+y d$ and $b=x d+y$. Attaching a trivalent vertex on the top says $b=x$. Solving, we see $y=-b / d$ and thus $b=b d-b / d$. Thus $d$ satisfies $d^{2}=d+1$ and we have

$$
x=b \quad \square
$$

Thus the pivotal subcategory generated by the trivalent vertex is the Golden Category. Now, composing with the crossing on top says that the crossing simplifies, and so the whole category is the Golden Category. In particular

$$
x=x \quad \square
$$

and a standard argument (rotate 90 -degrees and compose) shows the coefficients must be given by the usual Kauffman bracket formula ( $z=w^{-1}$ and $d=-z^{2}-z^{-2}$ ) and thus is one of the standard braidings on one of the Golden Categories.

We next have the following lemma, which, when combined with results from $\S 6.3$, is a more precise version of Lemma 3.8.
Lemma 6.73. Suppose that $C$ is a trivalent ribbon category with $d \neq 1$ and

$$
x^{-} \rightarrow-\frac{b}{d-1} \square^{-} \square^{-}=0
$$

Then one of the following occurs:

- C satisfies (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) for $v$ any primitive 12th root of unity (by symmetry, this yields two distinct relations, not four), $C$ satisfies no other instances of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ), and the crossing does not simplify as a sum of the above diagrams;
- $C$ is $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$; or
- $C$ is a quotient of $S O(3)_{q}$ for some $q$ with the usual braiding (including $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$ ).

Proof. We will follow the notation and techniques of Proposition 3.3. We apply the tetrahedral symmetry operator $R$ to the given relation to get

$$
\begin{aligned}
& -u^{-1} \square+u^{-1} \square-\frac{b}{d-1} \square^{-} u^{-2} \square=0 \\
& u^{-2} \square+u^{-1} \square-\frac{b}{d-1} \square^{-} u^{-2} \square
\end{aligned}
$$

(Recall that the trivalent twist rescales by $-u$, which is $-v^{6}$ in instances of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ).) Multiply the first equation by $-u^{-1}$ and then add to the second relation to make the $\square$ terms vanish. We obtain

$$
u^{-1} \square+u^{-2} \square-\frac{b}{d-1} \square^{-} u^{-2} \square^{-} u^{-1} \square+u^{-3} \square
$$

Unless $u$ is -1 , this says that $>$ simplifies. So we split into two cases.
If $>$ simplifies, then $\mathcal{C}$ agrees with $S O(3)_{q}$ from Definition 2.11 as a pivotal category for $q^{2}+q^{-2}=d-1$. (Without the assumption that the crossing simplifies, we would only have that the subcategory of graphs with no crossings agrees with $S O(3)_{q}$.) So we need only solve for all braidings for $S O(3)_{q}$, which yields only the usual braiding (with $q=v^{3}$ ) or when $d=2$ the additional braiding giving $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$ (see [MPS17, Example 8.6]).

If $>$ does not simplify, then $u=-1$. To derive an instance of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ), we pick a value of $v^{-4}=\lambda \in\left\{1, \omega, \omega^{2}\right\}$ and sum the above three relations. When $\lambda=1$, the sum is equal to zero. When $\lambda \in\left\{\omega, \omega^{2}\right\}$ then $v$ is a primitive 12 th root of unity as desired.

It remains to show in this last case that $\mathcal{C}$ does not satisfy another instance of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ), so suppose it does. That would give us a three-dimensional space of relations between the six diagrams
![img-60.jpeg](img-60.jpeg)
(The two prior relations had two different eigenvalues under the action of $R$, so a third relation cannot be a linear combination of the two.) Since the crossing does not simplify, the three diagrams
![img-61.jpeg](img-61.jpeg)
are linearly dependent. But this contradicts Lemma 6.72, since in the Golden Category the crossing simplifies.

This argument interacts in an interesting way with Lemma 3.8, which was proved in a similar way. It's possible for $\mathcal{C}$ to satisfy (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) for $v= \pm i$ and also satisfy the given relation, but then it follows that $\mathcal{C}$ also satisfies two additional (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) relations for $v$ primitive 12th roots of unity. Indeed this happens for $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$ and $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$. (The reason that the additional relation has $v= \pm i$ is that $-v^{6}$ is the trivalent twist.)

Along with Lemma 2.18, we have the following corollary.
Corollary 6.74. If $\mathcal{C}$ is a trivalent ribbon category, and the four diagrams
![img-62.jpeg](img-62.jpeg)
are linearly dependent, then one of the following occurs:

- $\mathcal{C}$ satisfies two instances of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) for $v$ a primitive 12th root of unity and no other instances of (QEJac- $\alpha$ );
- $\mathcal{C}$ is $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$; or
- $\mathcal{C}$ is a quotient of $S O(3)_{q}$ with the usual braiding (including $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$ ).

Remark 6.75. Note that if $\mathcal{C}$ satisfies even one instance of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) for $v$ a primitive 12th root of unity, then (QECross- $\alpha^{\prime}$ ) guarantees a relation between
![img-63.jpeg](img-63.jpeg)
and hence the corollary applies and either $\mathcal{C}$ satisfies two instances of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) for $v$ a primitive 12th root of unity and no other instances of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ), or $\mathcal{C}$ is $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$, or $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$. The main example we know of in the first case is $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$. But note this has $\operatorname{dim} \operatorname{Sym}(t)_{4}=4<5$. We believe

that with the stronger assumption $\operatorname{dim} \mathcal{C}(4) \leq 4$ then $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$ is the only example at $v$ a primitive 12th root of unity but since the proof is long we will not give it here. On the other hand, in the first case of the Corollary if $\operatorname{dim} \mathcal{C}(4)=5$ we do not know how to get any control over the case where the five diagrams
![img-64.jpeg](img-64.jpeg)
are linearly independent and so there is no simple relation relating the two crossings.
Proposition 6.76. If $\mathcal{C}$ is a trivalent ribbon category and the six diagrams
![img-65.jpeg](img-65.jpeg)
span a space of dimension 4 or smaller, then one of the following occurs:

- $\mathcal{C}$ satisfies two instances of (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) for $v$ a primitive 12th root of unity and no other instances of (QEJac- $\alpha$ );
- $\mathcal{C}$ is $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$;
- $\mathcal{C}$ is a quotient of $S O(3)_{q}$ with the usual braiding (including $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$ ); or
- $\mathcal{C}$ is a quotient of $\left(G_{2}\right)_{q}$ with the usual braiding.

Proof. If the first four diagrams are linearly dependent then we're in one of the first three cases by the previous lemma. Otherwise, we have relations simplifying both the crossing and the square in terms of the first four diagrams. This means that $\mathcal{C}$ is generated by the trivalent vertex and $\operatorname{dim} \mathcal{C}(4) \leq 4$, and thus by a modification of [MPS17, §5] we see that $\mathcal{C}$ is a quotient of $\left(G_{2}\right)_{q}$ as a pivotal category. By [Kup94, §2.3] (see also [MPS17, §6]), after possibly replacing $q$ with $q^{-1}$ (which doesn't change the pivotal category) we may assume the braiding on $\left(G_{2}\right)_{q}$ is the standard one.

Specifically, in [MPS17] we only considered non-degenerate trivalent categories, but this can be avoided as follows. The argument that the pentagon reduces still applies, so all small faces reduce, and non-elliptic diagrams span all $\mathcal{C}(k)$. If the 10 non-elliptic diagrams in $\mathcal{C}(5)$ are independent then Kuperberg [Kup94] says that $\mathcal{C}$ is a quotient of $\left(G_{2}\right)_{q}$. If there's a relation between these ten diagrams, the relation must be negligible. By [MPS17] either there's a single relation and the category is a quotient of $\left(G_{2}\right)_{\mathcal{C}_{10}}$, or the non-degenerate quotient of $\mathcal{C}$ is an $A B A$ category which contradicts $\mathcal{C}$ being braided.

Corollary 6.77. If $\mathcal{C}$ is a trivalent ribbon category with $\operatorname{dim} \mathcal{C}(4) \leq 5$ which satisfies (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) for some $v$ which is not a primitive 12th root of unity, then the six diagrams
![img-66.jpeg](img-66.jpeg)
span $\mathcal{C}(4)$.
Proof. If the given diagrams do not span $\mathcal{C}(4)$ then they span a space of dimension 4 or fewer, and Prop. 6.76 applies. Since $\mathcal{C}$ satisfies (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) for some $v$ which is not a primitive 12th root of unity, the first case is impossible, and in all the other cases the given diagrams span.

We can summarize much of this as follows.
Corollary 6.78. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a trivalent ribbon category with small 4-box space. Then we have the following as ribbon categories (with their usual braidings).

- If $\operatorname{dim} C(4)=2$, then $C$ is the golden category.
- If $\operatorname{dim} C(4)=3$, then $C$ is $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$ or a quotient of $S O(3)_{q}$ (including $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$ ).
- If $\operatorname{dim} C(4)=4$, then $C$ is a quotient of $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$, a quotient of $\left(G_{2}\right)_{q}$, or another category with $v$ a primitive 12th root of unity.

Proof. If $\operatorname{dim} C(4)=2$, then the three diagrams in Lemma 6.72 are dependent and $C$ is the golden category (and $v$ is a primitive 5th or 10th root of unity).

If $\operatorname{dim} C(4)=3$, then the four diagrams in Corollary 6.74 are linearly dependent, so we get one of the two desired possibilities or $v$ is a primitive 12th root of unity. But in the latter case, those four diagrams already span $C(4)$ (since we are not in the golden category), so the crossing simplifies, contradicting Lemma 6.73.

Similarly if $\operatorname{dim} C(4)=4$, we can apply Proposition 6.76 .
6.5. Some results when $v$ is a root of unity. Let $\zeta_{n}=e^{2 \pi i / n}$ be a primitive $n$th root of unity.
6.5.1. The case $v= \pm 1$. Throughout this section we assume WLOG $v=1$. The results in this section are closely related to those in [Mou22], but we do not assume that the category is symmetric.

Recall $t=\frac{b-[5] \alpha}{\{2\}}=\frac{b}{2}$. We also have that $0=[5] b=-\alpha(d+\{8\})$, so we split into two cases based on whether $\alpha=0$.

Lemma 6.79. There are no trivalent ribbon categories $C$ satisfying (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) with $v=1$ and $\alpha \neq 0$.
Proof. By Proposition 3.7, (QESq- $\alpha^{\prime}$ ) holds and says that
![img-67.jpeg](img-67.jpeg)

But $d+\{8\}=0$ so $d=-2$, and this case is excluded by Lemma 3.5.
Lemma 6.80. If $v=1$ and $\alpha=0$ and the four diagrams
![img-68.jpeg](img-68.jpeg)
are linearly dependent, then $C$ is $S O(3)$, and in particular satisfies the classical Jacobi, anti-symmetry, and exceptional relations.

Proof. By Corollary 6.74, $C$ must be a quotient of some $S O(3)_{q}$ or is $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$. But $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$ is excluded by Lemma 6.71 at $v=1$. Then we must have $q=v^{3}=1$, and so it is a quotient of classical $S O(3)$, which satisfies all the classical exceptional relations. Since $S O(3)$ is semisimple it has no non-trivial quotients other than itself.

Proposition 6.81. If $C$ is trivalent ribbon category satisfying (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) with $v=1, \alpha=0$, and $\operatorname{dim} C(4) \leq 5$, then $C$ is symmetric and satisfies the Jacobi and anti-symmetry relations.

Proof. Anti-symmetry is immediate from $v=1$. (See Remark 1.21.)
(QEJac- $\alpha$ ) says that the Jacobi relation holds using an overcrossing. Composing this relation with the undercrossing shows that the Jacobi relation also holds using an undercrossing.

Since $\operatorname{dim} C(4) \leq 5$, the following six diagrams are linearly dependent:
![img-69.jpeg](img-69.jpeg)

More specifically, there is a relation between them that is an eigenvector of $90^{\circ}$ rotation with eigenvalue $\pm 1$. By Lemma 6.80 we may assume that the first four terms are linearly independent, so the coefficient on the positive crossing can be normalized to 1 :

$$
( \pm)+x(x \pm)+y(x \pm)=0
$$

If the + sign holds, we can attach an $>$ to the top and use the Jacobi relations to get

$$
x \square+\left(\frac{b x}{2}-2\right) \square+(2+y)>+b y \square=0
$$

Subtracting this relation from its rotation we get

$$
\left(\frac{b x}{2}-y-4\right)(\square-)<
$$

By our linear independence assumption, this relation must be trivial, so we see that $y=0$ and $x=8 / b$. But capping off our original relation we get $0=2+b x+(d+1) y=2+8=10$, which is a contradiction. So the relation cannot have rotational eigenvalue +1 .

Now we turn to a - sign in Eq. (32) and apply the same argument. We get

$$
-x \square+\left(\frac{x b}{2}-y\right) \square+y>--b y
$$

which anti-symmetrizes to

$$
\left(\frac{x b}{2}-y\right)(\square-)<
$$

which implies that $x=0$ and $y=0$.
Thus we see that the crossing must be symmetric, and in particular (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) becomes exactly the usual Jacobi relation.

The next proposition is essentially due to Cvitanović [Cvi08, Chapter 17] and Vogel [Vog11, §7.5]. (Both authors had much earlier statements.)

Proposition 6.82. If $C$ is a trivalent symmetric ribbon category satisfying the Jacobi and antisymmetry relations and $\operatorname{dim} C(4) \leq 5$, then $C$ satisfies the relations of the classical exceptional series.

Proof. Since $\operatorname{dim} C(4) \leq 5$ there must be a linear dependence between the six diagrams
![img-70.jpeg](img-70.jpeg)

We claim that WLOG the coefficient on the square is non-zero and hence can be normalized to 1. Indeed otherwise there's a relation between the other five diagrams, which by Lemma 6.80 can be assumed to have non-zero coefficient on the crossing. By Lemma 3.5 this relation must also have a non-zero coefficient on $>$ or $>$, and thus if we use this formula to simplify the crossing in the Jacobi relation we get a linear relation with a non-zero coefficient on the square.

Moreover, since the square is rotationally invariant, there must be such a relation which is a rotational eigenvector with eigenvalue 1:

$$
0=\square+x>x+y(x \quad \square \quad \square)
$$

Multiplying this by a crossing and using the Jacobi relation we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
0 & =\square-\frac{b}{2}+x \quad \square+y \quad \square+z \quad \square+ \\
& =\square+z+\left(-2 y-\frac{b}{2}\right)+y \quad \square+x
\end{aligned}
$$

If these two relations are distinct, then Proposition 6.76 applies, and the only case with $v=1$ is classical $S O(3)$ (note that there is no trivalent category $\left(G_{2}\right)_{\zeta_{3}}$ ), which satisfies the classical exceptional relation. Otherwise, we have $x=z$ and $y=-\frac{b}{6}$.

Capping off this relation gives $0=b^{2}+x-\frac{b^{2}}{6}+x(1+d)=(2+d) x+\frac{5 b^{2}}{6}$, so we have $x=-\frac{5 b^{2}}{6(2+d)}$. This gives the classical exceptional square relation.

Combining the previous results we have the following corollary.
Corollary 6.83. If $C$ is trivalent ribbon category satisfying (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) with $v=1$, and in addition $\operatorname{dim} C(4) \leq 5$, then $C$ satisfies the relations of the classical exceptional series.

Remark 6.84. One can think of the classical exceptional series as a limit of the quantum exceptional series where you set $w=v^{\lambda}$ and then take the limit as $v$ goes to 1 .

# 6.5.2. The case $v$ is a primitive third or sixth root of unity. 

Proposition 6.85. If $C$ is trivalent ribbon category satisfying (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) with $v$ a primitive third or sixth root of unity and $\operatorname{dim} C(4) \leq 5$, then after possibly rescaling the self-duality, $X$ is a G2(d) algebra in $C$.

Proof. WLOG we take $v=\zeta_{3}$. Since $v$ is not a 10th root of unity, $\alpha$ is non-zero. Also $b+[3] \alpha=$ $b \neq 0$. Equation (QECross- $\alpha^{\prime}$ ) says that the braiding is symmetric.

Then (QESq- $\alpha^{\prime}$ ) becomes

$$
x+\frac{\sqrt{-3}}{2 \alpha}(x)+y-\frac{1}{2}(y)+z
$$

If we rescale the self-duality to make $b=1-d$, we then have $\alpha=\frac{[5] b}{d+[8]}=-\sqrt{-3}$ and get exactly the classical $G 2$ relation from $\S 6.2$.

In particular, it follows from $\S 6.2$ that $C$ has a quotient that is $S O(3)$ or $G_{2}$.
Remark 6.86. To see the classical $G 2$ relations as a limit of $\mathrm{QExc}_{v, w}$ as $v \rightarrow \zeta_{3}$, we need to rescale $b$. If you rescale $b$ appropriately, then you can set $v=\zeta_{3} w^{\frac{1-d}{v}}$ and take the limit as $w \rightarrow 1$ to recover the classical $G 2$ relations. See also Proposition 6.103.
6.5.3. The case $v$ is a primitive fourth root of unity. Since $v$ is not a 10th root of unity, $\alpha$ is nonzero. We have that $d+2=\frac{-2 i b}{\alpha}$. We split into cases based on whether $b+[3] \alpha$ vanishes. In the case where $b+[3] \alpha=0$, we make the additional assumption that the 4 -box space is non-degenerate.

Proposition 6.87. If $C$ is a trivalent ribbon category satisfying (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) with $v=i$ and $b+[3] \alpha \neq$ 0 , then after possibly rescaling the self-duality, $X$ is an F4(d)-algebra object in C. In particular, $C$ has a quotient that is one of the examples from Table 8.

Proof. Since we assume $b+[3] \alpha \neq 0$, by (QECross- $\alpha^{\prime}$ ) the crossing is symmetric. (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) becomes

$$
\square+\square+\square=\alpha i(\square+\square)+
$$

If we rescale the self-duality so that $\alpha i=1 / 2$, then $b=(d+2) / 4$ and we have exactly the classical $F 4$ relation.

Proposition 6.43 then says $d$ is one of the values in Table 8 or $d \in\{2,0,-2\}$. The value $d=0$ is ruled out in the definition of a trivalent category, and at $d=-2$ the trivalent vertex vanishes. At $d=2$, there is a quotient to $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$, but this is excluded because it satisfies $b+[3] \alpha=0$.

Since we do not know whether the classical $F 4$ relation is sufficient for evaluating all closed diagrams, we do not know whether the quotient above is the non-degenerate quotient or whether we need to add more relations.

Remark 6.88. To see the classical $F 4$ relations as a limit of $\mathrm{QExc}_{v, w}$ as $v \rightarrow i$, we need to rescale $b$. If you rescale $b$ appropriately, then you can set $w=i v^{\frac{v-d}{12}}=i v^{-\eta}$ and take the limit as $v \rightarrow 1$ to recover the classical $F 4$ relations. See also Proposition 6.100.

Lemma 6.89. If $C$ is a trivalent ribbon category satisfying (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) with $v=i$ and $b+[3] \alpha=0$, then $\alpha=-\frac{b i}{2}, d=2, t=0$, and the following relations hold:
![img-71.jpeg](img-71.jpeg)

If in addition $C$ is symmetric, then after rescaling the self-duality $X$ is an F4(2)-algebra object in $C$.
Proof. This follows immediately from specializing Eqs. (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) and (QESq- $\alpha^{\prime}$ ), respectively.
Lemma 6.90. If $C$ is a non-degenerate trivalent ribbon category with $\operatorname{dim} C(4) \leq 5$ satisfying (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) with $v=i$ and $b+[3] \alpha=0$, then $C$ is $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$.

Proof. By Corollary 6.77, the diagrams
![img-72.jpeg](img-72.jpeg)
span $C(4)$. Thus we can check whether an element is negligible by pairing it with the above 6 diagrams. In particular it is easy to verify that
![img-73.jpeg](img-73.jpeg)
is negligible, and hence by non-degeneracy must be zero. Now Corollary 6.74 says that $C$ must be $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$ or a quotient of $S O(3)_{q}$ with the usual braiding. By Lemma 6.66, the latter only satisfies (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) with $v=i$ when $q=i$ (so $C$ is $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$ ), in which case $b+[3] \alpha=-3 b \neq 0$.

There are some interesting degenerate examples with $v=i$ and $b+[3] \alpha=0$, which we will return to in future work.

6.5.4. Symmetric trivalent ribbon categories. We can combine previous results to get the following, essentially due to Cvitanović [Cvi08].

Proposition 6.91. Suppose that $(C, X, \tau)$ is a symmetric trivalent ribbon category with $\operatorname{dim} C(4) \leq$ 5 and $\operatorname{dim} X=d$. Then after rescaling the self-duality appropriately one of the following holds for the symmetrically self-dual object $X$ with multiplication defined by $\tau$ :

- $X$ is an Sym-algebra object, and hence $1 \oplus X$ is a normalized commutative Frobenius algebra object in the additive completion of $C$.
- $X$ is a G2-algebra object, and hence $1 \oplus X$ is a Hurwitz algebra object in the additive completion of $C$.
- $X$ is an F4-algebra object, and hence $1 \oplus X$ is a cubic Cayley-Hamilton fordan algebra object in the additive completion of $C$.
- $X$ is a Lie algebra object satisfying the classical Exceptional relations.

Proof. By Proposition 3.3 and Lemma 3.5, we satisfy (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) for some $v, \alpha$. Since $C$ is symmetric, looking at the trivalent twist we see $v^{6}= \pm 1$, and hence $v$ is a 12 th root of unity. If $v= \pm 1$ then $X$ is a Lie algebra object satisfying the classical Exceptional relations by Corollary 6.83. If $v$ is a third or sixth root of unity then $X$ is a G2-algebra object by Proposition 6.85. If $v$ is a primitive 4th root of unity and $b+[3] \alpha \neq 0$ then $X$ is an $F 4$-algebra object by Proposition 6.87. If $v$ is a primitive 4 th root of unity and $b+[3] \alpha=0$ then by Lemma $6.89, X$ is again an $F 4$-algebra object (using for the first time that $C$ is symmetric in addition to $v^{12}=1$ ).

The only remaining case is where $v$ is a primitive 12th root of unity. Then (QECross- $\alpha^{\prime}$ ) implies

$$
1+\frac{b}{d-1}(-\frac{b}{d-1}=0
$$

This relation together with symmetry implies that $X$ is an Sym-algebra object.
Note that the symmetric assumption was essential in the case where $v$ is a primitive 12th root of unity, see Remark 6.75 for more details.

Remark 6.92. The above cases are not mutually exclusive. Indeed both $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{3}\right)$ and $(\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$, $V_{1}^{-}$) appear in both the $F 4$ and $\operatorname{Sym}(t)$ families, and $S O(3)$ appears in both the G2 and Exceptional families. In these overlapping cases some care must be taken in applying the above result, because the appropriate rescaling of $\tau$ might be different in the two families! This occurs in the case $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$ where the Frobenius algebra structure from Remark 6.26 and the cubic CayleyHamilton Jordan algebra structure from Example 6.61 are not isomorphic.

Remark 6.93. Proposition 6.91 can be proved more directly. In a symmetric ribbon category the symmetric group $S_{n}$ acts on $C(n)$. Since symmetric group representations are easier to study than braid group representations this can be analyzed directly. First, $C(3)$ is 1-dimensional so $S_{3}$ either acts by the trivial or sign representation. Since $\operatorname{dim} C(4) \leq 5$, the six diagrams
![img-74.jpeg](img-74.jpeg)
span a representation of $S_{4}$ of dimension at most 5 . It is easy to see what 6 -dimensional representation of $S_{4}$ these six diagrams span: the first three span the induced representation of the trivial representation of the group $G=(\mathbb{Z} / 2)^{2} \rtimes \mathbb{Z} / 2$ while the latter three span the induced representation from a certain 1-dimensional representation of $G$ which depends on the twist. Corollary 6.94. Suppose that $G$ is a compact Lie group of non-zero dimension, and $X$ is a non-trivial symmetrically self-dual irrep $G$ of dimension $d$ with $\operatorname{dim} \operatorname{Hom}\left(X^{\otimes 3}, 1\right)=1$ and $\operatorname{dim} \operatorname{Hom}\left(X^{\otimes 4}, 1\right) \leq$ 5. Then one of the following holds:

- The map $X \otimes X \rightarrow X$ is anti-symmetric, and $X \cong \mathfrak{g}$ is a Lie algebra with a compatible G-action.
- The map $X \otimes X \rightarrow X$ is anti-symmetric, and $X$ is not the adjoint representation, in which case there's a Hurwitz algebra $A \cong 1 \oplus X$ with a compatible $G$-action.
- The map $X \otimes X \rightarrow X$ is symmetric, in which case there's a cubic Cayley-Hamilton Jordan algebra $A \cong 1 \oplus X$ with a compatible $G$-action.

Proof. This follows from Proposition 6.91, except that in the case where the multiplication is commutative, we need to rule out the possibility that $1 \oplus X$ is a commutative Frobenius algebra object. In this case we would have a functor $\operatorname{Sym}(t) \rightarrow \operatorname{Rep}(G)$, and since the latter is unitary, this functor factors through the quotient by negligible morphisms. Hence we get a functor $\operatorname{Rep}\left(S_{n}\right) \rightarrow \operatorname{Rep}(G)$ for some $n$, from which it follows that $G$ is a subgroup of $S_{n}$ which contradicts the assumption on $\operatorname{dim} G$.

An interesting corollary here is that there must be some cubic Cayley-Hamilton algebra attached to each Lie group in the $F 4$ family. We already explicitly identified these algebras, so this doesn't provide any new results, but it explains why we got lucky and were able to find such Jordan algebras.
6.6. Specializations to exceptional Lie algebras. Suppose that $V$ is a self-dual representation of a quantum group ribbon category such that there's a unique map $V \otimes V \rightarrow V$ and such that $V \otimes V$ has no more than 5 distinct summands all of which are multiplicity free. Then Theorems 1 and 2 apply, and some instance of the quantum exceptional relations must hold. In this section we explicitly identify a number of quantum group categories as quotients of the quantum exceptional series following this outline.

We begin by proving classical specialization, following [EN19, Thm. 2.1], [Kup96, Thm. 5.1], and [GSZ23, Thm. 5.3].
Definition 6.95. We say that a simple Lie (super)algebra $\mathfrak{g}$ is an Exceptional Lie algebra if it appears in Table 7, an expanded version of Table 1 (excluding the trivial group). We let $\lambda=-6 / h^{\vee}$ where $h^{\vee}$ is the dual Coxeter number. For the Lie algebras in the table (excluding $\mathfrak{o s p}(1 \mid 2)$ ), let $\mathfrak{f}$ denote the compact form of $\mathfrak{g}$ and consider the group $G_{\mathfrak{f}}=\operatorname{Aut}(\mathfrak{f})$ of Lie algebra automorphisms. Explicitly, this is the semidirect product of the adjoint form of the compact Lie group $K$ attached to $\mathfrak{f}$ by the group of Dynkin diagram automorphisms. Since the group of Dynkin diagrams automorphisms is discrete, the Lie algebra of $G_{\mathfrak{f}}$ is $\mathfrak{f}$. See Table 7 for more details about the values of $\lambda$, the groups, and the representations. As in $\S 2.2, \Delta$ is the ratio of the squared length of the long roots to the squared length of the short roots.

Recall that the Killing form (and hence any of the other normalizations we use for the inner product) restricted to $\mathfrak{f}$ is negative definite, and that any automorphism of $\mathfrak{f}$ automatically preserves the Killing form since it is defined by a matrix trace of compositions of brackets. Hence the construction of $G_{\mathfrak{f}}$ from $\mathfrak{f}$ follows exactly the procedure from $\S 6.1$.

Here $\mathfrak{o s p}(1 \mid 2)$ uses notation from $\S 2.5 .2$, and for other groups fundamental weights are ordered as they are in KM's quantum groups Mathematica package [Mor06]. In each case the representation is the adjoint representation. Also recall from $\S 2.4$ that we choose $q=q_{S}$ in our quantum group conventions.
