Proposition 6.96. Suppose that $\mathfrak{f}$ is the compact form of an Exceptional Lie algebra that is not $\mathfrak{G S p}(1 \mid 2)$. Then there is a full and dominant functor $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda} \rightarrow \operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{\mathfrak{f}}\right)$.

Proof. This is easy to check directly using the skein theoretic description of $S O(3)_{q}$ in the case $\mathfrak{g}=A_{1}$. In all other cases $\mathfrak{g} \otimes \mathfrak{g}$ is a sum of 5 distinct simple objects as a representation of $G_{\mathfrak{f}}$ (but not necessarily as a representation of $\mathfrak{g}$ ).

Using the Convenient form, we have that $\mathfrak{g}=V_{\theta}$ is a metric Lie algebra object in $\operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{\mathfrak{f}}\right)$, and thus takes a functor from the category of Jacobi diagrams $\mathrm{Jac}_{\mathbb{C}, \operatorname{dim}(\mathfrak{g}), 12}$. Thus, by Proposition 6.82, the classical exceptional relation with parameter $\lambda$ holds for some $\lambda$. By Lemma 3.14 we see that $2 \lambda$ and $2(1-\lambda)$ are the unique non-zero eigenvalues of the ladder operator on $\mathfrak{g} \otimes \mathfrak{g}$ not coming from the summands $\mathfrak{g}$ or 1 . But, by Corollary 2.9 , the eigenvalue on the summand $V_{2 \theta}$ is $-12 / h^{\vee}$. Thus (by the symmetry exchanging $\lambda$ and $1-\lambda$ ) we may take $\lambda=-6 / h^{\vee}$. Hence the functor descends to one out of $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda}$.

This functor is full and dominant by Proposition 6.5 and Remark 6.6.
We expect that Proposition 6.96 also holds for $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$ at $\lambda=-4$, but we do not prove that result here since we would need the appropriate version of Tannaka-Krein duality and the right analogue of compactness in the proof of Proposition 6.5.

In particular, the category of representations of the corresponding group on the right of Table 1 is the Cauchy completion of a quotient of $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda}$. This result is in the style of the first fundamental theorem of invariant theory; one would also like an explicit characterization of the kernel of this quotient, which we do not have. If $\operatorname{End}(1)=\mathbb{C}$ in $\operatorname{Exc}_{\mathbb{C}, \lambda}$, in particular if Conjecture 1.3 holds, then the kernel of this quotient can be characterized abstractly as the tensor ideal of negligible morphisms.

Now we turn to the quantum version, a more precise version of Proposition 1.16.
Proposition 6.97. With $\mathfrak{g}, \mathfrak{f}, G_{\mathfrak{f}}, \lambda$, and $\Delta$ from the exceptional family in Table 7, and for $q$ in some dense subset of $\mathbb{C}$ (in the complex topology), there is a full and dominant functor from $\mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}, q^{-\Delta / \lambda}, q^{-\Delta}}$ to the category of representations of $\operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{\mathfrak{f}}\right)_{q}$.

On the $\mathfrak{a}_{1}$ line, a fractional power of $q$ appears; any root will work, as discussed in $\S 6.3$. There is also a fractional power on the $\mathfrak{a}_{2}$ line, but recall that parameters $(v, w)$ and $(-v, w)$ give the same category.

Proof. First suppose that $G_{\mathrm{t}}$ is not $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)$. In addition, we have already analyzed the case $G_{\mathrm{t}}$ is $\operatorname{PSU}(2)$ in Lemma 6.66. Otherwise, let $V$ be the adjoint representation of $\operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{\mathrm{t}}\right)_{q}$, let the trivalent vertex be the deformation of the Lie bracket map $V \otimes V \rightarrow V$, and choose the Convenient normalization. Our main theorem applies, so (QEJac- $\alpha$ ) holds for an appropriate $v$ and $\alpha$. We can compute $v$ directly, as follows. The highest weight vector in the adjoint representation is a long root $\theta$, and thus by $\S 2.4$ and Table 2 the negative trivalent twist is $-v^{6}=-q^{(\theta, \theta+2 \rho)_{S} / 2}=-q^{h^{\vee} \Lambda}=$ $-q^{-6 \Delta / \lambda}$. (We can also double-check this using that the negative crossing acts on the cup by the positive twist, which is $v^{12}=q^{(\theta+2 \rho, \theta)_{S}}=q^{2 h^{\vee} \Lambda}$.) The negative crossing acts on the highest weight component $V_{2 \theta}$ of $V \otimes V$ by

$$
q^{-(\theta, \theta)_{S}}=q^{-2 \Delta}
$$

We would like to apply Lemma 3.12. First we need to verify that $(v, \alpha)$ as $v$ varies does not lie entirely on an excluded line from Lemma 3.12. This can be seen by, for instance, taking the limit of $d$ as $v \rightarrow 1$ : for the excluded lines we get 3 or -2 , which is not $\operatorname{dim} \mathfrak{g}$. Therefore, at all but finitely many values of $q$ we can apply Lemma 3.12, to see that, up to symmetry, we may take $w=q^{-\Delta}$. To see that we can take the correct root of $v^{6}$ and get $v=q^{-\Delta / \lambda}$, look near $q=1$ and use Lemma 3.14 and continuity; see also $\S 4$. We thus get a functor from $\mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}, v, \mathrm{w}}$ to $\operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{\mathrm{t}}\right)_{q}$.

By Corollary 6.9 the functor $\operatorname{Tr}_{\mathbb{C}} \rightarrow \mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C}, v, w} \rightarrow \operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{\mathrm{t}}\right)_{q}$ is given by rational functions, and by Proposition 6.10 this functor is full and dominant on a dense set.

The same result holds for $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)_{q}$ (with $\lambda=-4$ and $\Delta=4$ ). This can be easily checked directly using the skein theoretic description of $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)_{q}$. Alternatively, $\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)_{q}$ with its adjoint representation $V_{g}^{*}$ as a tensor generator is isomorphic to $S O(3)_{q}$ with $V_{(4)}$ as a tensor generator, and then the result can be deduced from Proposition 6.100 below.

Note that $\Delta$ appears because we used $q=q_{S}$; the formulas would be slightly nicer if we used $q=q_{L}=w^{-1}$. In addition, note that $v=q_{C}$, the $q$-variable corresponding to the Convenient form.

One can instead argue that a version of the previous result holds over $\mathbb{C}(q)$, but one needs to be a little careful in applying our main theorem since that field is not algebraically closed.

For $q$ in the dense set from Proposition 6.97, as before the category of representations of the corresponding group on the right of Table 1 is the Cauchy completion of a quotient of $\mathrm{QExc}_{\mathbb{C},-q^{-\Delta / \lambda}, q^{-\Delta}}$. If $\operatorname{End}(1)=\mathbb{C}$ in QExc, in particular if Conjecture 1.14 holds, then the kernel of this quotient can be characterized abstractly as the tensor ideal of negligible morphisms.

Remark 6.98. In particular, we see that if $\mathfrak{g}$ is Exceptional and not $\mathfrak{a}_{1}$, the braiding on the 4box space of $\operatorname{Rep}\left(G_{\mathrm{t}}\right)_{q}$ has an eigenvector for the braiding of eigenvalue -1 . This eigenvector corresponds to projection onto the simple summand of $\wedge^{2} \mathfrak{g}$ complimentary to $\mathfrak{g}$, named $X_{2}$ by Deligne. (In the case of $\mathfrak{a}_{1}$, that summand vanishes.) From the Kontsevich integral point of view, this follows from Lemma 2.10.

Proof. We follow the outline of Proposition 6.97, but the details are different. First suppose $d \notin\{-2,-1\}$. In the other cases, since $\operatorname{Rep}(G)_{q}$ satisfies the hypotheses of our main theorem, (QEJac-w) holds and we have a functor from $\mathrm{QExc}_{v, w}$ to $\left(\operatorname{Rep}(G)_{q}, V_{\mu}\right)$. Again a dimension argument shows we are not entirely in an exceptional line for Lemma 3.10, and so can apply Lemma 3.12. Note that $V_{2 \mu}$ is a summand of $\operatorname{Sym}^{2}\left(V_{\mu}\right)$ with eigenvalue $q^{-\langle\mu, \mu\rangle_{S}}$ for HTw. Comparing with the eigenvalues for HTw from Lemma 3.12, we see that (up to symmetries) we can take $w=q^{-\Lambda}$.

Similarly, from the symmetric product giving $V_{\mu}$ as a summand of $\operatorname{Sym}^{2}\left(V_{\mu}\right)$, we deduce that $-v^{h}=q^{\langle\mu, \mu+2 \rho\rangle_{S} / 2}$. To nail down which sixth root to take, observe that there is another summand $W_{v}$ of $\wedge^{2} V_{\mu}$, for which the eigenvalue of HTw must be $v^{2} / w^{2}=-q^{\langle\mu, \mu+2 \rho\rangle_{S}-\langle v, v+2 \rho\rangle_{S} / 2}$, so by the limit $q \rightarrow 1$ we see $v^{2}$ must be negative of a power of $q$. Up to symmetries we can thus take $v=i q^{\Lambda \eta}$ where $\eta=\frac{\langle\mu, \mu+2 \rho\rangle_{S}}{6\langle\mu, \mu\rangle_{S}}$. We need to relate this formula for $\eta$ to the formula in terms of $\operatorname{dim}\left(V_{\mu}\right)$ given in Definition 6.99. For this, take the dimension formula in $\mathrm{QExc}_{v, w}$ (also the quantum dimension of $V_{\mu}$ in $\operatorname{Rep}\left(\mathrm{G}_{\mathrm{q}}\right)$ ),

$$
d=-\frac{\Psi_{4}[\lambda+5][\lambda-6]}{[\lambda][\lambda-1]}
$$

and take the limit as $h \rightarrow 0$ with $q=e^{h}, w=e^{\Lambda h}$, and $v=i e^{\eta \Lambda h}$. We get

$$
\operatorname{dim}\left(V_{\mu}\right)=\lim _{h \rightarrow 1} d=-\frac{(-2)(2 i)(-2 \Lambda(1+6 \eta))}{(\Lambda)(-2 i)}=2(1+6 \eta)
$$

Remark 6.101. Note that $A_{2}$ with its adjoint representation is both an Exceptional Lie algebra and an $F 4$ Lie algebra. & \left(\zeta_{16}, \zeta_{32}^{-5}\right):\left(E 8, E_{6}, \zeta_{32}^{9}\right) \cong\left(F 4, F_{4}, \zeta_{32}^{9}\right) \\
& \left(\zeta_{16}, \zeta_{12}^{-3}\right):\left(E 8, G_{2}, \zeta_{32}^{3}\right) \cong\left(E 8, G_{2}, \zeta_{32}^{9}\right) \\
& \left(\zeta_{14}, \zeta_{21}^{-4}\right):\left(E 8, E_{7}, \zeta_{21}^{4}\right) \cong\left(G 2, G_{2}, \zeta_{42}^{11}\right) \\
& \left(\zeta_{14}, \zeta_{7}^{-1}\right):\left(E 8, A_{2}, \zeta_{7}\right) \cong\left(E 8, E_{6}, \zeta_{7}^{2}\right) \cong\left(F 4, A_{1}, \zeta_{28}^{9}\right) \\
& \left(\zeta_{14}, \zeta_{36}^{-4}\right):\left(E 8, E_{8}, \zeta_{35}^{4}\right) \cong\left(E 8, E_{8}, \zeta_{35}^{11}\right) \\
& \left(\zeta_{14}, \zeta_{28}^{-3}\right):\left(E 8, G_{2}, \zeta_{28}\right) \cong\left(F 4, C_{3}, \zeta_{28}^{9}\right) \\
& \left(\zeta_{14}, \zeta_{21}^{-1}\right):\left(E 8, F_{4}, \zeta_{42}\right) \cong\left(E 8, F_{4}, \zeta_{21}^{4}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Table 10. Conjectural isomorphisms between quantum group categories. These are the $49(v, w)$ parameters where the lines from the exceptional (a.k.a. E8), F4, and G2 families intersect, up to Galois conjugation and excluding degenerate parameter values. Specifically we exclude values where $v$ is a primitive root of unity of order $1,2,3,4,5,6,8,10,12, w= \pm 1, w= \pm v^{k}$ for $k=-5,6$, or $w= \pm i v^{k}$ for $k=-2,3$.
$\left(\operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2), V_{2}^{*}\right)$ appears as $\left(E 8, \operatorname{SOSp}(1 \mid 2)\right)$ and when quantized is isomorphic to $\left(A_{1}, V_{(4)}\right)$, appearing as $\left(F 4, A_{1}\right)$. Finally, $\left(A_{2}, V_{(1,1)}\right)$ appears as both $\left(E 8, A_{2}\right)$ and $\left(F 4, A_{2}\right)$; see Remark 6.101.

The same data can be seen graphically already in Figure 1, as the intersections of colored solid lines that are not also on dashed lines, except that the excluded line $v^{10}=1$ is not marked there.

Warning 6.104. In this discussion, we are taking our conjectural diagrammatic categories and semisimplifying them at the listed root of unity. In order to translate these conjectural equivalences into statements about the semisimplified category of tilting modules for the Lusztig quantum group we would need to know that the semisimplified diagram category and the semisimplified tilting module category were equivalent. Even in cases where such an equivalence is known at roots of unity, it will still fail for a few small roots of unity. So one should be especially skeptical about the conjectures below in the semisimplified tilting module setting if the root of unity is small.

Remark 6.105. The case of $F_{4}$ at level $4,\left(E 8, F_{4}, \zeta_{52}^{9}\right) \cong\left(F 4, F_{4}, \zeta_{52}^{7}\right)$ (circled in Figure 1) is especially interesting. This is a categorical version of the automorphism of the fusion ring of $F_{4}$ level 4 from [Gan02, §3.8]. Composing this equivalence with its own Galois conjugate gives a braided equivalence $\left(\left(F_{4}\right)_{4}, \zeta_{52}\right) \cong\left(\left(F_{4}\right)_{4}, \zeta_{52}^{25}\right) \cong\left(\left(F_{4}\right)_{4}, \zeta_{52}^{-1}\right)$ (with some permutation of the representations) and hence a braided reversing auto-equivalence of $\left(\left(F_{4}\right)_{4}, \zeta_{52}\right)$. This braided reversing auto-equivalence may be of interest to the study of exotic subfactors. NS and KM noticed that $F_{4}$ at level 4 has dimensions which are related to the dimensions of objects in the Extended Haagerup subfactor [BMPS12], and Edie-Michell [EM22, Question 7.2] strengthened this observation to ask whether the center of the Extended Haagerup fusion categories is an Evans-Gannon grafting [EG11] of $F_{4}$ level 4 using a braiding-reversing autoequivalence. Evans-Gannon grafting has not been rigorously defined at the level of ribbon categories, and moreover we need to assume the quantum sufficiency conjecture in order to construct the autoequivalence Edie-Michell requires. We will explain this in more detail in future work.

# Lean Focused Research Organization

abstract:
We find a single two-parameter skein relation on trivalent graphs, the
quantum exceptional relation, that specializes to a skein relation associated
to each exceptional Lie algebra (in the adjoint representation). If a slight
strengthening of Deligne's conjecture on the existence of a (classical)
exceptional series is true, then this relation holds for a new two-variable
quantum exceptional polynomial, at least as a power series near $q=1$. The
single quantum exceptional relation can be viewed as a deformation of the
Jacobi relation, and implies a deformation of the Vogel relation that motivated
the conjecture on the classical exceptional series.
  We find a conjectural basis for the space of diagrams with $n$ loose ends
modulo the quantum exceptional relation for $n \le 6$, with dimensions agreeing
with the classical computations, and compute the matrix of inner products, and
the quantum dimensions of idempotents. We use the skein relation to compute the
conjectural quantum exceptional polynomial for many knots. In particular we
determine (unconditionally) the values of the quantum polynomials for the
exceptional Lie algebras on these knots. We can perform these computations for
all links of Conway width less than $6$, which includes all prime knots with 12
or fewer crossings. Finally, we prove several specialization results relating
our conjectural family to certain quantum group categories, and conjecture a
number of exceptional analogues of level-rank duality.
